<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four EU Members Warned of Law Violation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission Friday
announced a decision to pursue infringement procedures against
Italy, Germany, Portugal and Belgium because the four European
Union (EU) members have violated rules on freedom to provide
services or freedom of establishment.
</P>
<P>
"As a result of obstacles preventing temporary employment
agencies based in other member states from offering their services
in Italy," the EU executive branch said, it had decided to refer
Italy to the European Court of Justice, the EU's highest
jurisdictional body.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the EU executive decided to refer Germany to
the EU court for discriminatory rules "concerning workers on
secondment from another member state."
</P>
<P>
The European Commission also decided to send reasoned opinions
to Germany and Portugal "concerning provision of services by
patent agents." Meanwhile, the EU executive is to send reasoned
opinions to Belgium "concerning discriminatory rules for the
registration of companies."
</P>
<P>
Under the EU Treaty, all the barriers "violate rules on freedom
to provide services or freedom of establishment," the commission
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
As for the registration of companies in Belgium, the director
or manager of a company must produce his permit if he is a EU
national residing in Belgium. However, if the director or manager
is a Belgian citizen, he is not required to provide proof of
residence.
</P>
<P>
"While this differential is not connected with the requirement
of residency as such, it amounts to discrimination on the basis of
nationality and is therefore incompatible with the principle of
freedom of establishment," the commission said.
</P>
<P>
The commission made the decision to send a reasoned opinion to
the Belgian authorities because it has not received a satisfactory
response to its letter of formal notice about this violation.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive is mainly responsible for drafting and
enforcing the EU's legislation. It has the right to decide to
refer any country to the EU court if it does not receive a
satisfactory reply from the country within two months after
sending the reasoned opinion, a serious warning for a violator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
