<HEADLINE> IMF Return Vital to Economic Recovery: Kenyan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, Aug 6 (Xinhua) -- Improved relations with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) was key to Kenya's economic
recovery, Oduor-Otieno, an official with the country's Finance
Ministry, said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Oduor-Otieno, who was appointed as permanent secretary of the
ministry two weeks ago, told press that combating corruption and
ending inefficiency in government top his team's agenda.
</P>
<P>
"We have to improve our relations with donors, especially the
IMF. We have to improve our efficiency, project management, and
we have to deal with corruption," he said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF suspended a 205-million-U.S. dollar loan package to
Kenya in 1997 due to its concerns over corruption and poor
governance in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
So far talks on a resumption of the IMF loan has not restarted
because the IMF argued that it needs to see tangible
anti-corruption measures.
</P>
<P>
Oduor-Otieno said budgetary discipline and infrastructure were
also crucial to invigorating the battered economy.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of Oduor-Otieno and Richard Leakey two weeks
ago was part of what Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi described
as the first phase of Kenya's recovery strategy. Kenya's gross
domestic product growth is forecast at 1.6 percent in 1999 from
1.8 percent last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
