<HEADLINE> Waldner Beats Kong in Men's Quarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion
Jan-Ove Waldner edged out Chinese 1995 world titlist Kong Linghui in
the world table tennis championships here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old Swede, world champion in 1989 and 1997, counted on
his experience and deceptive serves to win the match 22-20, 13-21,
21-18, 19-21, 21-15 in the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
Kong, who had only won once in his seven encounters with Waldner,
virtually broke down as the Swede took five points in a row to lead
10-5 in the deciding set.
</P>
<P>
Waldner, the only player in the world to have won a "Grand Slam"
of Olympic, world championship and World Cup titles, will take on
Chinese giant-killer Ma Lin.
</P>
<P>
Ma Lin, who brought down world No. 1 Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus
in the fourth round, entered the last four with a 21-13, 21-18, 21-8
victory over South Korean Kim Taek Soo.
</P>
<P>
Olympic title holder Liu Guoliang didn't give a chance to Sweden's
1991 world champion Jorgen Persson, winning 21-7, 21-10, 21-15.
</P>
<P>
"I played to my standard," said Liu. "I have confidence to win
the gold medal."
</P>
<P>
Refering to Kong-Waldner match, Liu said Kong didn't return well to
the Swede's serves.
</P>
<P>
"But I was not surprised at all when either of them won," the
Chinese fast-attacker added. "They are the best players of the world
and both played to their best today."
</P>
<P>
Liu will meet Austrian Werner Schlager in the semifinals on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Schlager beat two-time World Cup Zoran Primorac of Croatia 21-18,
19-21, 17-21, 21-11, 21-14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
