<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Invites Warring Afghan Factions to Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran has said it is inviting the
Taliban and its opposition forces in Afghanistan to implement
agreements reached at the "six plus two" meeting in Tashkent,
Uzbekistan in July.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing conflicts in Afghanistan have no military solution,
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said to the official
Islamic Republic News Agency here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan's six neighbors - China, Iran, Pakistan,
Tajikistan, Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan - and the United States
and Russia, well-known as the "six plus two" informal group, have
agreed to improve coordination and efforts for a common approach
toward the settlement of the Afghan crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Experience of conflicts in the past few days in Afghanistan
has brought about nothing but bloodshed, homelessness, and
devastation," Kharrazi said, referring to the lastest Taliban
offensive in which it seized a key airbase of the opposition
forces.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that around 5,000 Taliban fighters, backed by
recruits from Pakistan and some Arabs, took part in the
offensive, the first in 10 months.
</P>
<P>
Iran supports the opposition forces while Pakistan backs the
Taliban, the religious students' movement that has won control of
most of the country in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The international community has been trying to foster a peace
process in the war-stricken country but has not immediately
achieved results.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said Iran is fully ready to help a peace process and
urges Pakistan to do its best in bringing the Taliban to peace
talks in a bid to end bloodshed in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
