<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Drought in Four U.S. States Worst Ever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Friday that the current drought in four northeastern states
in the country is the worst ever recorded for agriculture and it
threatens to cripple businesses and communities.
</P>
<P>
The drought is the worst ever for farmers in Maryland,
Delaware, New Jersey and Rhode Island states, Clinton said before
leaving the White House for a weekend trip to Arkansas and
Missouri states.
</P>
<P>
Maryland and New Jersey have imposed state water restrictions.
</P>
<P>
"Such a natural calamity can have devastating consequences, not
only for farmers, but for small businesses and communities that
depend upon a thriving agricultural sector, and for the electric
power system so vital to our nation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The federal government has worked hard to help drought-stricken
farmers, Clinton said. "We must do more. It is our duty as a
national community."
</P>
<P>
The White House will convene a task force of affected federal
agencies "to coordinate our efforts and focus our attack on this
problem," Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
