<HEADLINE> Iran to Export More Electricity to Azerbaijan, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran will be able to export more
electric power to neighboring Azerbaijan and Turkmenistan when its
power line installations complete by this yearend.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Energy Miniter Habibollah Bitaraf said Friday that
power grid connections to the two countries through Ardabil
province in the west and Mazandaran province in the east are now
underway.
</P>
<P>
Iran's capacity for electricity export now stands at 250
megawatts, and Azerbaijan, Turkey, and Armenia are receiving
electricity by hooking up to power grids in Iran's provinces of
East and West Azarbaijan, Bitaraf was quoted by the official
Islamic Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran is potentially capable of increasing its capacity
of power production by up to 2,000 megawatts each year if
sufficient investments are made available.
</P>
<P>
Iran needs 2 billion U.S. dollars in investments to boost its
electric power production.
</P>
<P>
The country generated 102 billion kilowatt-hours of electricity
in the past Iranian calendar year which ended March 20, and would
increase its output to 108 billion kilowatt-hours by this yearend.
</P>
<P>
The country's electric power generating capacity was reported
at 25,400 megawatts, ranking the 21st in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
