<HEADLINE> U.S. Remains World's Biggest Arms Provider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States remained the
world's biggest exporter of arms in 1998, accounting for about a
third of the total, despite worldwide demand has been slumping,
the U.S. Congressional Research Service said Friday in an annual
review of arms sales.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the United States led in new arms deals, with 7.1
billion U.S. dollars, up from 5.7 billion U.S. dollars in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Germany ranked second, with 5.5 billion U.S. dollars in new
sales, and France third, with 3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The value of all new arms sales worldwide in 1998 was 23
billion U.S. dollars, up from 21.4 billion U.S. dollars the year
before.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said that the trend in terms of arms sales
has generally been downward, particularly among developing
nations, which are the biggest buyers of weapons. Since 1995,
total arms sales declined by 23.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis and low oil prices have contributed
to the decline in demand, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Even though the world total arms sales declined after the end
of the Cold War, the United States increased its sales to
developing countries to 4.6 billion U.S. dollars in 1998 from 2.6
billion U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The biggest buyers of arms last year was Saudi Arabia, with 7.9
billion U.S. dollars in new sales. The United Arab Emirates ranked
second at 2.5 billion U.S. dollars. Malaysia ranked third, with
2.1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russia has seen its exports steadily declining since
the end of the Cold War. In 1991, it sold 8.2 billion U.S. dollars
in arms. In 1998, the total declined to 1.7 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
