<HEADLINE> FAO to Focus on Post Harvest Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) announced Friday that it has set up
a global post-harvest forum called PhAction, which is expected to
help make up post-harvest losses.
</P>
<P>
The Rome-based FAO believes that post-harvest losses are
dramatic in developing countries where loss of cereals is between
10 and 20 percent and of fruits and vegetables as high as 20 to
100 percent.
</P>
<P>
"There is no question that decreasing these post-harvest losses
could mean more food for tens of millions of consumers," the U.N.
agency said in a press release distributed at the U.N.
headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
It estimates that just a 10 percent savings of post-harvest
losses in Asian rice would mean a savings of 5 million tons of
food a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
