<HEADLINE> Russia, Japan Hold Consultations in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin is
expected to sign "a weighty package" during his official visit to
Japan later this year, the Foreign Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The package would include agreements on scientific and
technical cooperation, cultural ties and air traffic, the ministry
said in a statement released after the end of bilateral
consultations in Moscow, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Grigory Karasin and his
Japanese counterpart, Minoru Tamba, conducted the consultations.
</P>
<P>
Both ministers emphasized that Yeltsin's visit will be "a
milestone in promoting bilateral partnership," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Karasin and Tamba also co-chaired sub-commissions concerned
with border demarcation and joint economic activity in the
southern Kuril Islands within the framework of the bilateral
commission for concluding a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
They "discussed prospects for broadening bilateral ties in the
context of building long-term partnership" and confirmed the
"shared intention to actively pursue all aspects of bilateral
dialogue," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed the situation on the Korean
Peninsula. They warned against "exerting pressure" and called for
using "political methods only" to resolve the Korea issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
