<HEADLINE> Kenyan Businesses Yet to Recover Year after Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The affected businesses are still
struggling to recover one year after the August 7 bombing of the
U.S. embassy in Kenya's capital Nairobi, observers here said.
</P>
<P>
For Kenya's tourism sector, the situation in the past year has
been a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
"Tourism is about perception, it thrives on information and
when you perceive a place as insecure, you simply stay away,"
said Fred Kaigua, chief of the Kenya Association of Tour
Operators.
</P>
<P>
Small businesses, already struggling to survive in a flagging
economy, were aggravated by the terrorist blast, which claimed
more than 200 lives and injured over 5000.
</P>
<P>
"It was a big setback and the impact on small businessmen was
colossal," said Victor Pratt, chairman of the Kenya Management
Assistance Program.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of people lost their jobs, lost their income. The
government lost taxes and productivity of the economy dropped
considerably," said Pratt.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive of the Investment Promotion Council Joseph
arap Ng' ok put the economic and social cost of the bombing at 10
percent of Kenya's gross domestic product (GDP) in today's price.
</P>
<P>
Ng'ok held that small traders within the vicinity lost complete
businesses, stocks, productive assets and customers.
</P>
<P>
"These mainly comprised bus operators, kiosk owners , newspaper
vendors and hawkers and their losses are unrecoverable," Ng'ok
added.
</P>
<P>
Economic loss suffered by big Kenyan companies located in the
destroyed buildings was also a huge blow to the country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
The attack, which was reported worldwide, made foreign
investors hesitant to visit Kenya, resulting in a drop in foreign
exchange earnings, said Ng'ok.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the United States Agency for International
Development released some 300,000 U.S. dollars for small and
medium businesses affected by the blast.
</P>
<P>
Already 200,000 dollars have reached 44 organizations. A loss
assessment has been undertaken by Kenya Management Assistance
Program and further disbursements start this month.
</P>
<P>
However, some of the people affected believe it may be mere
symbolism. Some 210 businesses are expected to benefit, which
means if the money were distributed equally, each firm would get
only 135 dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
