<HEADLINE> Annan Hails Sudanese Ceasefire Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Friday voiced his welcome to a Thursday decision by the
Sudanese Government on a comprehensive ceasefire throughout the
African country.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said that the ceasefire "is essential for the
provision of much needed humanitarian assistance to hundreds of
thousands of civilians" affected by the ongoing conflict in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by his spokesman, Annan said, "I welcome
the announcement made yesterday by the Government of Sudan
declaring a comprehensive ceasefire throughout the Sudan for a
period of 70 days."
</P>
<P>
"A ceasefire is essential for the provision of much needed
humanitarian assistance to hundreds of thousands of civilians,
mostly women and children, affected by the ongoing conflict," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese Foreign Ministry, in a statement issued in the
capital Khartoum, declared Thursday a unilateral ceasefire across
the country, which took effect at midnight Thursday and would
expire on October 15.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry statement said the government made the
move to "facilitate the delivery of humanitarian assistance to all
areas in need," and "the government hopes the rebel movement would
reciprocate by a similar move."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Annan called upon the rebel Sudanese People's
Liberation Movement (SPLM) to consider extending the scope of this
ceasefire and thus contribute to the creation of an enabling
environment for humanitarian operations in the Sudan," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The SPLM and its troops agreed on the extension of a
humanitarian-oriented ceasefire for Bahr-El-Ghazal, western and
central Upper Nile in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
"I count on the continued support of the Government and the
SPLM for the unhindered and safe provision by U.N. humanitarian
agencies and NGOs (non-governmental organizations) of relief to
all those in need of humanitarian aid throughout the country,"
Annan said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The ceasefire, first agreed with the government last year,
effectively broke down last month during peace talks in the
Kenyan capital of Nairobi, which is aimed at ending the 16-year
civil war in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Rebels fighting for the predominantly Christian and animist
south want increased autonomy in their region. More than 1.5
million people are believed to have died since the insurrection
broke out in 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
