<HEADLINE> Turkish Officer Killed by PKK Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- One Turkish officer was killed and
one soldier wounded in an armed attack Thursday night by rebels of
the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in eastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
A group of PKK rebels attacked a Turkish military team in Catak
town of Van province, causing the casualties, the semi-official
Anatolia News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Imprisoned PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan has called on his
followers to "end the struggle" and "withdraw from the Turkish
territory."
</P>
<P>
The PKK has reportedly responded that they would obey Ocalan's
call, but vowed to defend themselves when being attacked.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel, however, brushed aside the
appeal for peace from Ocalan, who was sentenced to death on the
charge of treason.
</P>
<P>
"Orders such as 'end the struggle' or 'go on with the struggle'
will not have any affect on our resolution to end terrorism," he
said.
</P>
<P>
PKK has been waging a separatist campaign for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey since 1984. Conflicts between
the Turkish security forces and the PKK rebels have claimed over
37,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
