<HEADLINE> Suspects of U.S. Embassy Bombing Still at Large </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- One year after the twin bombings
of the U. S. Embassies in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam, the
terrorists behind the blasts are still at large.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the U. S. Department of State published in
Kenyan major newspapers photographs of eight suspects responsible
for the August 7 bombing, which indiscriminately killed 224
innocent civilians and injured more than 5000.
</P>
<P>
Public places have also been posted with the notice, in which
the U.S. government is offering a reward of five million U.S.
dollars for information leading to the capture or conviction of
Saudi millionaire Bin Laden and other suspects.
</P>
<P>
Bin Laden is on the U.S. Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)
's "Ten Most Wanted" list.
</P>
<P>
Living somewhere in Afghanistan under the acknowledged
protection of the ruling Taliban, the 41-year-old son of a Saudi
construction magnate was formally indicted in America late last
year as ringleader of the bombing conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
Bin Laden's Al Qaeda (the base in Arabic) "remains actively
engaged in planning terrorist activities", according to the U.S.
State Department.
</P>
<P>
Other fugitive suspects on the poster are Atef, Fadhil,
Mohamed, Ghailani, Ally, Swedan and Fazil.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the intensive worldwide hunt for those suspects has
yielded tangible results. Some 17 suspects have been charged with
murder in the United States in connection with the bombings.
</P>
<P>
Five of the suspects are in custody in New York, while three
more are in custody in Britain pending extradition.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has handed over two suspects to the FBI. They are among
those charged in a New York court with murder.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, the trial of another two suspects was stalled due
to lack of crucial evidence from accomplices who are still at
large.
</P>
<P>
Although the U.S. government has made efforts to improve
security at its facilities overseas and combat terrorism, alerts
at American overseas diplomatic missions were sounded repeatedly
in the past year.
</P>
<P>
About 70 consulates and embassies have been temporarily
shuttered, resulting in a record number of facility closures.
</P>
<P>
U.S. experts said that the two east African embassies were easy
targets for terrorists because they are among the least secure of
Washington's 265 diplomatic outposts.
</P>
<P>
By the standards of an embassy security report issued in 1980s,
so far only 40 to 45 make the grade, said Michael Sheehan, the
State Department's counter-terrorism coordinator.
</P>
<P>
An alarm was raised again only a week before the anniversary of
the terrorist attacks, when security guards had to fire two
shotgun shells into a battered box parcel left behind within the
perimeter of the temporary building of the U.S. embassy on the
outskirts of Nairobi by an unidentified messenger.
</P>
<P>
Fears that the suspicious package was an explosive device
caused the security alert for over an hour. All people in the
mission were evacuated to the basement.
</P>
<P>
The parcel was found to contain a swimming suit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
