<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Gov't Rejects Request to Open Gambling Center in Lyon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The French government rejected
Friday a request by the gambling business group Partouche to open
a gambling center in the central city of Lyon.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry said that it rejected the request because
there would be too many slot machines as compared with the
traditional gambling tables in the envisaged center.
</P>
<P>
It also said that Partouche failed to present a detailed plan
to financially aid the cultural programs of the city, which was
obligatory for a gambling business.
</P>
<P>
France had banned gambling business until 1988, when the
parliament adopted a law allowing big tourist cities with more
than 100,000 inhabitants and big cities with 500,000 inhabitants
to open gambling centers.
</P>
<P>
If the request is approved, Lyon will become the first big
French city to have a gambling center.
</P>
<P>
Lyon's mayor, former Prime Minister Raymond Barre, supports the
project, which envisages to open the gambling center in an
underground part of a Hilton hotel by the side of the Rhone River,
amid a highly prosperous international business district.
</P>
<P>
Another French big city, Bordeaux, also plans to open a
gambling center with the Accor group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
