<HEADLINE> Cuba's New World Record Holders Sets Sight on Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Cuba's Hidalberto
Quintero Aranda, who set a new weightlifting world record Thursday
at the Pan American Games, has set his sight firmly on the Sydney
2000 Games.
</P>
<P>
"I'm looking forward to Sydney," Aranda said here Friday. "The
Pan Am gold is only a step towards the 2000 Games."
</P>
<P>
The Winnipeg Concert erupted into cheers yesterday as the
packed crowd witnessed the first world record broken in the 13th
Pan Am Games.
</P>
<P>
The standing ovation broke out when Aranda lifted 205.5kgs in
the clean and jerk, improving the world standard, set by the
international weightlifting federation on January 1,1998, by 0.5kg.
</P>
<P>
The judges unanimously declared Aranda's 205.5kgs clean-and-
jerk attempt good, making the Cuban athlete the world record
holder in the men's 77kgs class.
</P>
<P>
The world record came during the two-stage clean and jerk phase
of the contest for 24-year-old Aranda, who weighed in at 76.55kgs.
It came during the final minutes of the competition, when the
Cuban had run out of challengers other than himself and the
previous best mark.
</P>
<P>
He did it by upping his first clean-and-jerk attempt to 190kgs
from 185kgs, then moving up to 200kgs and finally to 205.5kgs in
the final attempt.
</P>
<P>
Aranda's combined total for the clean and jerk and snatch came
to 355kgs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking through an interpreter, the new champion told
reporters that he first tried to beat the world record at 1998
weightlifting meet in Mexico but couldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
Besides Sydney Olympics, Aranda also intends to defend his
title at the world championships in Athens later this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
