<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Tax Cut Not To Become Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
declared Friday that the Republican bill of 792 billion dollars
will not become law.
</P>
<P>
"This tax cut will not become law," he said, repeating his
determination to veto the bill.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he is willing to consider limited tax cuts using
projected budget surpluses, but only after Social Security and
Medicare are safeguarded for the future, public debt is paid
down and sufficient levels of spending are ensured for education,
defense, enrironment protection and other programs.
</P>
<P>
"That is how we ought to determine the size of the tax cut," he
said. "The amount should not be decided by politics, but by
arithmetic."
</P>
<P>
Defying Clinton's repeated vow to veto it, Republican lawmakers
Thursday pushed through the bill, which would be the largest tax
cut since President Reagan's in 1981.
</P>
<P>
The Senate approved the bill 50-49 after it cleared the House
221-206. Both the House and Senate adjourned until September 8.
</P>
<P>
Republican lawmakers decided to take their case for the tax cut
to their constituencies during the August congressional recess.
</P>
<P>
With little chance of becoming law, the bill will serve mainly
as a defining issue between Republicans and Democrats in the 2000
struggle for control of Congress and the race for the White House.
</P>
<P>
"There is a dramatic difference between Democrats and
Republicans in this capital city, and this is the dividing line,"
said Republican Representative Bill Archer, chairman of the House
Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
Republican leaders will not send the bill to Clinton to avoid
immediate veto while they are away for the August recess.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said Thursday night that no matter when the bill arrives
at the White House, "I will have no choice but to veto it
immediately."
</P>
<P>
The bill would trim the bottom 15 percent income tax rate to 14
percent in 2003 and reduce the other rates by 1 percentage point in
2005.
</P>
<P>
Relief from the "marriage penalty" that affects millions of
two-income couples would begin in 2001.
</P>
<P>
The estate tax would be repealed gradually starting in 2003, and
capital gains taxes would be cut from 20 percent to 18 percent for
most investors retroactive to Jan. 1, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
