<HEADLINE> Namibia Urges to Revoke Rebel Leader's Refugee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Namibia's Foreign Affairs department said Muyongo's interviews
with the international media had left no doubt that he was behind
this week's rebel attack on Katima Mulilo, Caprivi's main town in
northern Namibia.
</P>
<P>
He was granted as refugee in Denmark earlier this year after he
led hundreds of Caprivians into neighboring Botswana as part of
the secessionist bid.
</P>
<P>
At least 13 people were killed in clashes between rebels and
security forces at Katima Mulilo Monday. A state of emergency was
imposed in the area following the clashes. The situation there was
reported to become normal again.
</P>
<P>
Businesses in the Caprivi were exerting pressure on the
Namibian government to have the Ngoma border post with Botswana
reopened, the SABC report said.
</P>
<P>
They urgently needed goods imported from South Africa which had
been held back at the border post for the past few days, the
report said.  
