<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Okays U.N. Presence in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Friday unanimously decided to authorize the deployment of up to 90
military liaison personnel to help bring an end to the 11-month
conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council authorizes the deployment of up to 90
military liaison personnel, together with the necessary civilian,
political, humanitarian and administrative staff, to the capitals
of the States signatories" of a peace agreement, the resolution
said.
</P>
<P>
These military personnel will have a three-month mandate to
establish contacts and maintain liaison with the Joint Military
Commission (JMC) and all signatories to the July 10 cease-fire
agreement, to assist all parties concerned in developing
modalities for the implementation of the agreement, signed in
Lusaka, capital of Zambia, said the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The military observers are also to provide technical assistance
as required to the JMC, said the resolution, adding that they are
asked to provided information to the U.N. Secretary-General
regarding the situation on the ground, and "to assist in refining
a concept of operations for a possible further role of the United
Nations" in the implementation of the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said these military liaison officers are
required to secure from the parties guarantees of cooperation and
assurances of security for the possible deployment in-country of
military observers.
</P>
<P>
The resolution called upon all States and parties concerned to
ensure the freedom of movement, security and safety of United
Nations personnel in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council reaffirms the sovereignty, territorial
integrity and political independence of Congo (K), the former
Zaire, and all States in the region, said the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said the Security Council "welcomes the signing
of the Cease-fire Agreement on the conflict" in Congo (K) on July
10 in Zambia, which "represents a viable basis for a resolution of
the conflict" in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation Security Council "also welcomes the signing of
the Cease-fire Agreement on August 1, 1999 by the Movement for
Liberation of the Congo," and "expresses deep concern that the
Congolese Rally for Democracy has not signed the Agreement and
calls upon the latter to sign the Agreement without delay in order
to bring about national reconciliation and lasting peace" in the
country, said the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council "calls upon all parties to the conflict,
in particular the rebel movements, to cease hostilities, to
implement fully with the OAU (Organization of African Unity) and
the United Nations in the implementation of the Agreement to
desist from any act that may further exacerbate the situation,"
the resolution said.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was adopted after the Security Council met
Friday morning to consider a July 16 report from U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who raised the recommendations on
the deployment of these military liaison officers.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations hopes for thousands of international
peacekeepers and 500 military observers to help maintain a
cease-fire in the vast African nation once all the warring
parties agree to lay down their weapons.
</P>
<P>
Six African countries involved in the conflict, which broke out
in August last year in eastern Congo (K), signed the agreement in
Lusaka with the peace efforts from some African countries, the OAU
and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The signatories included the rebels' backers Rwanda and Uganda
as well as President Laurent Kabila of Congo (K), who was
supported by troops from Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia.
</P>
<P>
But internal disagreements prevented some rebel leaders from
signing the peace accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
