<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) Salim Ahmed Salim Friday
deplored secessionist attempts in Namibia.
</P>
<P>
While meeting Namibian ambassador to Ethiopia Eddie Amkongo,
Salim pointed out that many African countries face genuine
economic and social problems. "These, however, cannot be resolved
by armed and violent means."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that secessionis attempts in Namibia are both
unfortunate and totally unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general conveyed, through the ambassador, his
condolences and those of the OAU to the government and people of
Namibia and especially to the families of all those who lost their
lives in rebel attacks.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his sincere hope for the speedy return of
normalcy in Namibia and affirmed the OAU's full support for the
Namibian government's efforts in promoting the welfare and
progress of all Namibians and the development of the country as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of people were reportedly killed and wounded following a
rebel attack on August 2 on a military garrison and a radio
station in the Caprivi region of Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma declared a state of emergency
soon after the attacks. After days of fierce of fighting, the
Namibian government troops have recaptured all the key points
seized by the secessionists.
</P>
<P>
The tense situation in the Caprivi region is returning to
normal, the latest sources reaching here said.  
</P>
