<HEADLINE> IRA Denies Smuggling Plans, Murder Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Irish Republican Army (IRA)
denied Friday its leadership sanctioned plans to smuggle guns into
Ireland from the U.S., following the indictment of four members of
an alleged smuggling ring by a Florida court.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by Irish national broadcaster RTE, the
guerrilla group said no breach of the IRA ceasefire was involved
in last week's killing of Charles Bennet in Belfast and that the
ceasefire remains intact.
</P>
<P>
The killing cast fresh doubt over IRA claims over the
ceasefire. Bennett was shot in the head on 30 July.
</P>
<P>
The IRA statement, which said Bennett's killing "was not a
breach of the cessation," fell short of an outright denial that it
shot him.
</P>
<P>
"I believe to some extent that they are accepting that there
was some responsibility there, that there was some involvement,"
said RTE correspondent Charlie Bird, who was given the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement came a day after two men from Northern Ireland
appeared in court in the U.S. and pleaded not guilty to illegally
posting guns and bullets from Florida to the Republic of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
However, it is believed here any ruling by the British and
Irish governments that the IRA had broken its ceasefire could lead
to the expulsion of its political ally Sinn Fein from Northern
Ireland's peace process and power-sharing institutions set up
under an agreement singed in April 1998. 
</P>
