<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Enact Law to Regulate Oil Sector: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Minister of
Energy and Minerals Abdallah Kigoda announced Friday that the
government plans to enact a law and establish an authority to
regulate petroleum business before June next year.
</P>
<P>
Kigoda said this in a motion tabled to the National Assembly
(parliament) in the central city of Dodoma following complaints
made by members of parliament over the increase of petroleum
prices, which would trigger hiking of commodity prices
countrywide.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the proposed legislation and authority, the
government is preparing temporary regulations to control the
liberalized sector, reports reaching here quoted Kigoda as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said there are fears that big operators of petroleum
products in the world are colluding to fix prices of essential
goods, frustrating fair trade practices.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, the Tanzanian government is unable to control
prices of petroleum because it does not produce crude oil while
prices of the refined oil is being fixed by importers, the energy
minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Kigoda said the increase of petrol in the world market by
around 50 percent and depreciation of the Tanzanian shilling
against the dollar has further complicated the situation.
</P>
<P>
He promised that the government will continue to review its
petrol price structure in a bid to ensure effective competition in
the sector.
</P>
<P>
But he noted fixing of petrol prices is a complex exercise that
needs enough time before the government could make major
decisions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an MP criticized the government for failing to
control prices of petroleum thus making the public shoulder extra
burdens.
</P>
<P>
MP Anthony Diallo of the ruling Tanzanian Revolutionary Party
told a press conference in Dodoma that the rise of petroleum
prices was in fact caused by the increase of many taxes and poor
irrational price structures.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is making excuses that the increase of
petroleum prices was simply caused by world prices and the
government actually has the capacity to control petroleum prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
