<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Nominate Ferguson as Fed Vice Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Friday he will nominate Roger Ferguson to be vice chairman
of the Federal Reserve, the U.S. central bank.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson, 47, is currently serving as a member of the Fed
board. If confirmed by the Senate, he would replace Alice Rivlin,
who stepped down last month, and become the first black to serve
as vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
"He is superbly qualified. he has served well and I am very
excited about the prospect of his service," Clinton said of
Ferguson, a banking expert who holds a law degree and a doctorate
in economics from Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
The Fed board is composed of seven members who form the nucleus
of the 12-member Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) that sets
U.S. monetary policy. The FOMC comprises the seven board members,
the president of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York and four
presidents of the other 11 Fed regional banks who serve on a
rotating basis.
</P>
<P>
Fed members have a key say in the direction of U.S. interest
rates, a particularly sensitive question at the moment as the
financial markets weigh whether the FOMC will raise rates to slow
the economy at its next meeting on August 24.
</P>
<P>
The board currently has two vacancies: the vice chairman's job
as well as an ordinary board member slot. On Thursday, Clinton
said he planned to nominate former New York banker Carol Parry to
fill the board member vacancy.
</P>
<P>
After finishing his studies, Ferguson worked at the prominent
New York law firm of Davis Polk &AMP; Wardwell from 1981 to 1984 and
then moved to McKinsey &AMP; Co. where he became a partner and
specialized in banking as well as payments systems.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson was confirmed as a Fed board member in October 1997,
becoming the third black to serve on the panel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
