<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Feature: Hebron Under Siege </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEBRON, WEST BANK, August 6 (Xinhua) -- On a main road leading
to Hebron, a dozen of cars and trucks were lining up in front of
roadblocks, with their drivers being questioned by Israeli
soldiers armed with automatic rifles. Almost all of the cars were
seen making U-turns to go back.
</P>
<P>
"The city is closed," the soldiers told the drivers, including
foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
The drivers were also informed that if they really wanted to go
into the city, they had to take a big detour.
</P>
<P>
Military siege of Hebron entered the third day in the wake of
a shooting incident Tuesday night, in which two Jewish settlers
were lightly wounded in an ambush by unidentified gunmen.
</P>
<P>
Israeli soldiers sealed off the city, barring Palestinians
except Hebron residents from entering and preventing all
Palestinians from leaving.
</P>
<P>
One of the most ancient cities in the region, Hebron got
her name from a Hebrew word meaning "friendly." In Arabic, the
city is called Halilee, which means "the beloved." But the city
has turned out to be a flashpoint of conflicts since it was
divided into two parts controlled by Israel and the Palestinians
respectively, under an interim accord signed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
About 450 Jewish settlers live among more than 150,000
Palestinians in the city, with tensions and conflicts constantly
flaring between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Whenever there is any conflict, Israeli soldiers seal off the
city and impose a curfew on the Israeli-controlled part, barring
the 30,000 Palestinian residents in this part from leaving their
houses.
</P>
<P>
Three days after the latest curfew was imposed, life remained
stagnate in the Israeli-controlled part, with all shops closed,
not a single pedestrian seen on the streets, except patrolling
soldiers and military jeeps. The only sign of Arab existence was
the children peeking from behind windows and Arabic music coming
from inside buildings.
</P>
<P>
In the Palestinian-controlled area, however, residents said
they have got used to this kind of situation and have found ways
to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
Abu Faris, a 33-year-old English teacher, said the siege is not
a problem at all. In the last three days, he managed to travel
freely between his home in Hebron and the village of Halhoul just
outside the city, where he keeps an art-craft shop.
</P>
<P>
"Every morning I parked my car near the checkpoint, then
I bypassed the roadblock on foot, and then I took a taxi
to my shop," he smiled.
</P>
<P>
In face of the bitter reality, he kept a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
"Life is really nice here. We will not be bored," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked what was the meaning of the closure if people
could still enter and leave the city by taking detours, Abu
Faris said: "they just want to make trouble for us."
</P>
<P>
For Abu Faris and other Palestinians in Hebron, the closure
of the city is a reminder that peace between Israel and the
Palestinians is still far away.
</P>
<P>
Hopes for a quick revival of the stalled peace process raised
by the election of Ehud Barak as Israeli prime minister in May
have faded since Barak ran into dispute with Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat on the implementation of
the U.S.-brokered Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
Though he pledged to carry out the Wye accord signed and then
frozen by his hard-line predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu last year,
Barak has been seeking to make some changes to its
implementation by blending parts of it with the final-status talks
aimed at a permanent settlement, but he has been turned down by the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The shooting incident Tuesday night is the first of its
kind since Barak took office early last month.
</P>
<P>
The PNA, which condemned the attack, said that Barak could
prevent such terror attacks by implementing the Wye agreement,
which calls on Israel to cede lands, release Palestinian
prisoners and build safe passage between the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990807.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Promises to Start Implementation of Wye </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak promised on Friday that Israel would start further
implementation of the Wye agreement within three weeks.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Television Channel One, Barak said
the timetable has been worked out with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser
Arafat last month.
</P>
<P>
Barak said the timetable was first set by him and Mubarak and then
Arafat concured with it.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the PNA signed the Wye accord in the United States
last October. The interim pact requires Israel to hand over to the
Palestinians another 13.1 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Benjamin Netanyahu, hard-line predecessor of Barak, carried out
the first phase of the three-stage withdrawal, but then suspended
the accord, accusing the Palestinians of failing to fulfill their
security commitments.
</P>
<P>
After assuming office last month, Barak pledged to implement
the second stage of withdrawal, but proposed to combine the third
withdrawal with the final status talks, an idea flatly rejected by
the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Barak has also said that if the Palestinians did not want the
proposal, he would fulfill his peace commitment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
