<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syria on Wednesday started commercial production of
a new oil field at a daily capacity of 5,000 barrels of light oil
and 200,000 cubic meters of gas.
</P>
<P>
Syria produces more than 600,000 barrels of oil a day, of which
320,000 barrels are exported. Syria's total gas production is
estimated at 12.5 million cubic meters a day.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT -- Officials of the U-Kuwait Co. for Petrochemicals said
the company plans to increase its production from 86 million
dinars (281 million U.S. dollars) to 306 million dinars (1 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The decision, agreed upon by shareholders of the company, could
be fully implemented in the third quarter of the current year, the
company said in a written statement on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti government owns 45 percent of the shares of
U-Kuwait, the first joint venture in the petrochemical sector in
the country, while a United States company owns a similar
percentage. The remaining percentage is owned by Bobyan for
Petrochemicals, of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- China has expressed its interest in bidding for
tenders to rebuild two Beirut power plants destroyed in last
month's Israeli air assaults, the local An Nahar newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Al Mustaqbal daily has reported that Swiss ABB company had
won the tender to rebuild Jamhour, one of the two bombarded
suburban plants.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will take part in the 46th Damascus
international fair scheduled to be held on August 28 through
September 10, the country's Middle East News Agency reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will display in the fair household appliances, including
refrigerators and washing machines, metal products, foodstuffs,
textiles and furniture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
