<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Tries to Resolve Wrangle in Congolese Rebel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 6 (Xinhua) --Zambian Minister of State House
Eric Silwamba had separate meetings Thursday with rival rebel
leaders of the Congolese Rally for Democracy (CRD) to resolve the
wrangle in the major rebel group.
</P>
<P>
Silwamba's meetings with the CRD political and military leaders
took place separately in Goma and Kisangani of the the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC), reports reaching here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I have been in Goma, and Kisangani where I met political
leaders. The message is the same everywhere: Congolese people want
peace," Silwamba was quoted as saying in Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
"I will report to President (Frederic) Chiluba what I have seen
during this trip," he said.
</P>
<P>
In May this year, the Congolese Rally for Democracy split into
two factions. Emile Ilunga ousted Wamba and became the new
leader of CRD. After the wrangle broke out Wamba moved from
eastern Goma to northern Kisangani and has been insisting that he
is still the leader of the rebel group.
</P>
<P>
Silwamba noted that Wamba was no where to be seen. "I will
also submit all the RCD texts relating to Wamba's removal, then my
president will draw due conclusions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Because the power struggle within CRD, the CRD and the Movement
for the Liberation for Congo (MLC) did not sign the cease-fire
agreement signed in Lusaka on July 10 by all the six warring
countries involved in the 11-month war in the central African
country.
</P>
<P>
However, MLC leader Jean-Pierre Bemba signed the ceasefire
agreement here last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Wamba and MLC are allegedly backed by Uganda while Rwanda backs
the one led by Illunga. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
