<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Requires Release of Hostages in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Executive Secretary of the Economic
 Community of West Africa States (ECOWAS) Lansana Kouyate Friday
called for the "unconditional release" of over 30 hostages still
being held by former putschists in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The hostages "should be released unconditionally," the ECOWAS
chief said in Nigerian capital Abuja, reminding the putschists of
the need to respect the July 7 agreement.
</P>
<P>
The hostage takers claimed that their leader is being held by
the Foday Sankoh-led Revolutionary United Front (RUF) which signed
a peace agreement with the government in Togolese capital Lome on
July 7.
</P>
<P>
Through two of the released hostages, the putschists in
Freetown demanded the release of Johnny Koromah, leader of the
military junta that ruled the country for nine months before they
were flushed out by the ECOWAS-sponsored west Africa peace-keeping
force ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The rebels Thursday had released several hostages including two
U.N. officials, one Reuters reporter and one clergy man.
</P>
<P>
The development is believed to be related to the intensive
negotiations underway between the rebels and Sankoh's group and
the Sierra Leonean government.
</P>
<P>
Christo Johnson who was among the freed reportedly said in
Freetown Friday that all the hostages were well and that their
captors wanted food and medicine among other demands.
</P>
<P>
Johnson together with other hostages was seized Wednesday in
the Okra Hills region, about 65 km east of the country's capital
Freetown by soldiers loyal to a military junta that supplanted
elected President Tejan Kabbah in 1997.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 people including U.N. observers, ECOMOG officials,
 journalists, and other personnels were believed to be taken
hostages by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The kidnappers said through the released hostages that they
would release the hostages if the Lome peace agreement was revised
to give them and their leader Koromah more say in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The rebels said they were not satisfied with the peace deal
because the RUF, a dominant part of the rebels, seems to gain more
than their ally, the former military junta combatants, in the
peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
