<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Urges Dialogue in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Friday urged Afghan parties to the fighting to end
hostilities, stressing that the conflict would end only through
peaceful dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The conflict can never be resolved through force, Annan said in
a statement issued by his spokesman Fred Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
A peaceful dialogue would lead to national reconciliation and
the formation of a genuinely representative government acceptable
to all Afghans, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
He called on all Afghan parties including neutral groups and
individuals as well as countries with influence to work together
and with the U.N. to put an end to the present fighting and to
resume serious negotiations to establish peace in the country and
security in the region.
</P>
<P>
Annan's appeal came one day after the Security Council made a
similar call on warring factions in the central-west Asian country
to stop their senseless self-destruction and resume serious
negotiations under U.N. auspices.
</P>
<P>
According to the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR), the Taliban's recent offensive against the Northern
Alliance has displaced between 100,000 and 140,000 over a six-day
period.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan has been listed as one of the biggest refugee
sources in the world with 2.1 million Afghans in Iran and 1.6
million in Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
