<DOCNO> XIE19990807.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Protests against UNMIK Customs Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia has lodged
strong protest against customs control in boder crossings by the
United Nations Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK),
according to a U.N. Security Council document distributed Friday.
</P>
<P>
Instructed by his government, Yugoslav envoy Vladislav
Jovanovic lodged the protest in a letter to the president of the
U.N. Security Council on August 2.
</P>
<P>
Jovanovic, Charge d'affaires of the Permanent Mission of
Yugoslavia to the U.N., said UNMIK has established customs control
over four border crossings on Yugoslavia's border with Albania and
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
He listed the border crossings as those at Djieneral Jankovic,
Globocica, Cafa Prusit and Vrbnica.
</P>
<P>
"The customs proceedings in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia
are regulated by federal laws for the entire territory of the
country," said the letter, adding that "taking any of its parts
out of the unified jurisdiction constitutes a flagrant violation
of the provisions of Security Council resolution 1244(1999)".
</P>
<P>
UNMIK set up such customs control "without any agreement with
or the participation of competent Yugoslav authorities", the
letter said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990807.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Sets up Forum for Sharing Information on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Food
and Agriculture Organization (FAO) Friday announced the formation
of a global post-harvest forum in a response to growing needs for
information in post-harvest research and development, U.N.
officials said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
With the expansion of international food trade, and increased
importing and exporting of food products, a new dimension has
been added to the need for improving efficiency and minimizing
losses as food goes from the farmers' field to the consumers'
tables.
</P>
<P>
"Post-harvest activities used to focus on individual small
farmers who needed to preserve their harvested crops for
themselves and their families," said Francois Mazaud, senior
officer of FAO's post-harvest management group.
</P>
<P>
"Now innovative post-harvest systems allow farmers to add value
to their harvests while increasing income and generating off-farm
employment for people involved in the processing, transportation
and marketing of food products," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 10 founding institutes of the forum, known as PhAction,
will share information and work together to develop and deliver
innovative post-harvest systems, in collaboration with a range of
public and private sector partners in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
In the future, membership will be expanded to major regional
research bodies, key non-governmental organizations, agricultural
business centers and entrepreneurs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990807.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Move Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks moved lower
Friday as investors got much more worried about higher interest
rates after a strong report on U.S. employment.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 79.79 at
10,714.03, erasing more than half its 119-point gain Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The market plunged after the Labor Department reported that
employers added a stronger-than-expected 310,000 jobs to their
payrolls in July and average hourly earnings, a key gauge of
inflation pressures, increased by 3.8 percent in the same month
from a year ago. The report made investors believe that the
Federal Reserve would raise interest rates to preempt inflation
from the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan said two weeks
ago that the Federal Reserve must be especially alert to
inflation risks. If new data suggest that the pace of labor cost
and price increases will be picking up, the Federal Reserve will
act "promptly and forcefully" to fight against inflation, he said.
</P>
<P>
 Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 13.42 at 1,300.29 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index fell 17.87 at 2,547.96.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 6.55 at 611.04 and the Russell
2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.71 at 428.04. But the
American Stock Exchange index rose 1.83 at 777.92.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 2-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,980 down, 984 up and 536
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 696.11 million shares from 854.21
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
