<HEADLINE> King Kong Finds Solace in Men's Doubles Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese world No. 3
Kong Linghui, who fell a victim to defending champion Jan-Ove Waldner
of Sweden in the men's singles quarter-finals, found some solace as he
combined with Liu Guoliang to win the men's world doubles title here
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Kong, 1995 world champion and Olympic doubles gold medalist with
Liu, played extremely well in their 19-21, 21-16, 18-21, 21-10,
21-18 victory over fellow Chinese Wang Liqin and Yan Sen.
</P>
<P>
"I felt so disappointed after I lost to Waldner," Kong said. "I
told Liu that we must make it this time."
</P>
<P>
After splitting the first four sets, the deciding set went
virtually point by point until Liu and Kong attacked mercilessly to
clinch the match point.
</P>
<P>
Double Olympic gold medalist Liu Guoliang reached the singles
semifinals with an expected victory over 1991 world champion Jorgen
Persson of Sweden on Friday. He will take on giant-killer Austrian
Werner Schlager, who upset Croatia's two-time World Cup champion Zoran
Primorac in the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
Wang Liqin and Yan Sen, doubles champions in the ITTF Pro-Tour
Finals early this year, will return home empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
Wang suffered an early exit in the men's singles as he went down
to Frenchman Damien Eloi in straight sets. Yan Sen lost to Persson
in five sets on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Loss doesn't mean the end of the world," Wang said. "I will start
all over again."
</P>
<P>
"Wang's weakness is mentality, not skill," said Chinese head coach
Cai Zhenhua. "Technically, he is the best in the Chinese team but he
has to toughen his mind."
</P>
<P>
In the doubles semifinals, Liu and Kong downed Primorac and
Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus in four sets while Wang and Yan thrashed
South Korean duo Kim Taek Soo and Park Sang Joon easily.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Wang Nan beat 17-year-old Zhang Yining in an all Chinese
women's singles final.
</P>
<P>
Ma Lin paired up with Zhang Yingying to snatch the mixed doubles
title on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
