<HEADLINE> Wang Nan Lifts World Singles Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Little failure in form
and momentary slip in precision nearly threw off Wang Nan as she came
from the verge of defeat to beat fellow Chinese Zhang Yining in the
women's singles final of the world table tennis championships here on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
World Cup winner Wang Nan, 20, finally triumphed over the
17-year-old teammate 15-21, 14-21, 21-5, 21-12, 21-11.
</P>
<P>
Wang looked lackluster from the very beginning and should could
hardly concentrate on the game, losing first two sets without a
chance.
</P>
<P>
Wang unleashed strong forehand attacks from both wings, pressuring
her rival from the third set on.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't have a good start," said Wang. "But I came into game
gradually, and with a little luck, I won my first world singles
championship."
</P>
<P>
Wang Nan reached the final with a five-set win over South Korean
Ryu Ji Hye, while Zhang edged out fellow Chinese Li Nan, also in
five sets.
</P>
<P>
Wang finished runner-up to all-mighty Deng Yaping in last world
championships. Multi-world champion Deng opted out of the
championships to focus on her English language studies in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Zhang surprised many when her name was seen on the Chinese team
roster for this world championships in March. Geng Lijuan of Canada
and Ni Xia Lian of Luxembourg, former world champions for China, and
China's world No. 3 Li Ju and giant-killing Li Nan all fell victims to
Zhang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
