<HEADLINE> Congolese Ceasefire Threatened: Zimbabwean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Foreign Minister Stan
Mudenge said Saturday that the delays in the signing of the
ceasefire document by the Congolese Rally for Democracy and lack
of monitoring of the agreement was endangering the ceasefire in
the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a graduation ceremony at Morgenster Teachers
College in Masvingo of south Zimbabwe, Mudenge said the delays in
signing and lack of monitoring provided an opportunity to the
enemies of peace to restart the war, with all the terrible
consequences that would entail in the region, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The war in the DRC had reached a dangerous phase when we
achieved the peace agreement. It is still poised at that point,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are literally face to face with a potentially explosive
escalation in the war," he noted, adding he hoped that "everyone
will act responsibly and Africa and the world will assume their
full responsibility to ensure that the peace process continues to
hold."
</P>
<P>
According to the foreign minister, the most immediate obstacle
to overcome in restoring peace in the Congo was to resolve the
leadership rivalry within the Congolese Rally for Democracy.
</P>
<P>
The two factions which are led by Emile Ilunga and Ernest Wamba
dia Wamba had not agreed on who was entitled to sign on behalf of
the rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
"The result of this development is that the ceasefire is
incomplete and has not been monitored since July 10, 1999," said
Mudenge.
</P>
<P>
On July 10 of this year, leaders of the allied forces in the
Congo, Congolese President Laurent Kabila, the rebel groups and
leaders of Uganda and Rwanda met in Zambia to sign a ceasefire
document that would bring to an end of the one-year war in the
third largest African country.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state signed the agreement without the rebels, who
cannot decide which person would endorse the deal on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
However, Jean-Pierre Bemba, leader of the Liberation of Congo,
another rebel group, recently signed the ceasefire document,
bringing closer the prospects of peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
