<HEADLINE> France Opposes U.S. TMD Plan in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- France has expressed its opposition
to the U.S.-sponsored Theater Missile Defense (TMD) plan in East
Asia, saying it will trigger a new round of strategic nuclear arms
race, reported a French newspaper on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac is opposed to the U.S. plan and
holds "a full convergence" of views with China, the daily Le
Figaro quoted French presidential officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Over this issue, we stand by the side of the Chinese. The
American anti-missile missiles will reduce to nil the Chinese
defense and will launch a permanent race between sword and shield,
" said a presidential advisor at the Elysee presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine has written a letter to
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to explain the position
of France over what he called "a new specter of Cold War,"
according to Le Figaro.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said that the U.S. TMD plan, which includes deployment
of anti-missile missiles in Taiwan and Japan, will have
destabilizing effect in the Far East.
</P>
<P>
France suspects that the U.S. Defense Ministry, tacitly
supported by the U.S. Congress, is trying to justify the
development of anti-missile systems for Taiwan and Japan, as well
as for the United States itself.
</P>
<P>
"The United States Defense Ministry can no longer find the
pretexts in the Third World countries or in Russia. China is
therefore presented as a threat," the report quoted an
unidentified French official as saying.
</P>
<P>
But the real motive for relaunching a strategic nuclear arms
race in East Asia is the interests of U.S. military industrial
complex, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
