<HEADLINE> Trademark to Protect Scenic Cave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The company that manages
Huanglong Cave at the Zhangjiajie Scenic Spot in central China's
Hunan Province has decided to use its trademark to protect the
cave.
</P>
<P>
According to Ye Wenzhi, general manager of the Zhangjiajie
Huanglong Cavern Investment Co. Ltd., the company has applied to
the Trademark Bureau of the State Administration for Industry and
Commerce for registration of 37 literary items and 40 different
designs related to the cave.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese characters "Huanglong" or Yellow Dragon, bear the
connotations of "authority" and "luck" in Chinese culture, so they
might easily be used in names at other scenic areas, sites,
enterprises or buildings, the general manager explained.
</P>
<P>
"If the registration is approved by the bureau, it will be
illegal for operators of other scenic sites or enterprises to use
the words "Huanglong Cave" in either writing or graphic patterns
without permission," he went on.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that his company would redouble its efforts to
protect this intangible asset after the designation Huanglong Cave
is accepted as a trademark.
</P>
<P>
Huanglong Cave boasts more than 3,000 stalagmites and
stalactites, of which a stalagmite, which has growing for 200,000
years, were insured for 100 million yuan (about 12 million US
dollars) in April last year.
</P>
<P>
The company raked in well over 20 million yuan from sales of
tickets to tour the cave last year, according to the general
manager. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990807.0082 </DOCNO>
