<HEADLINE> S. African Bid for World Cup Applauded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- South African Sports
Minister Ngconde Balfour gave the South African 2006 World Cup Bid
Document the thumbs up in Johannesburg on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
South Africa are in the race with four other countries --
Germany, Morocco, England and Brazil -- to host the 2006 World Cup
and will hand over the Bid Document to world governing body, FIFA,
in Zurich on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"I am very happy with the document. I am proud of our sportsmen.
They did a marvelous job putting together this document," Balfour
said, quoted by South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
"We also drew up a document for the Cape Town Bid to stage the
Olympics, but the World Cup Bid Committee did very well."
</P>
<P>
He said there was nothing negative in the document and, in its
positively, reflected South Africa's readiness to host the world
event.
</P>
<P>
"I have still to take it to President Mbeki, but I have no
doubt in my mind it shows we have the capability to host such an
event and are prepared for the World Cup," Balfour said.
</P>
<P>
"We have learned a lot from hosting the Rugby World Cup in 1995,
the IAAF World Cup of Athletics last year and we also have the
upcoming All-Africa Games in September to learn more.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt in my mind it is Africa's call to stage the
World Cup."
</P>
<P>
The document chronicles the infrastructure of the country's
stadiums, telecommunication, accommodations and transport
capabilities, which show that South Africa will be able to stage
the event.
</P>
<P>
After the handing over of the Bid Document the next step in the
process is that FIFA will send inspectors to South Africa to check
the local infrastructure before the final decision is made in July
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
