<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Complete First North Pole Atmospheric Observation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Scientists of the
Chinese Arctic Expedition have completed their first observation
of the atmosphere at the North Pole.
</P>
<P>
They measured the changes in air pressure, humidity, wind speed
and wind direction in the atmospheric boundary layer, convection
layer and stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
According to expedition member Qu Shaohou, last Thursday the
expedition set up a 12 sq-m tent to carry out the observations at
73.25 degrees north latitude and 164.59 degrees west longitude.
</P>
<P>
The height of the atmospheric observation reached 600 m, and
the scientists observed a process of strong temperature inversion,
with changes of temperature of one degree centigrade every ten
minutes.
</P>
<P>
The scientists also collected data on solar radiation,
effective radiation on ice and reflective radiation.
</P>
<P>
Qu said the data obtained is important for research into the
interaction among the sea, ice and atmosphere at the edge of the
Arctic Ocean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
