<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze Pollution Control Efforts Paying Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Intensified pollution control
efforts on the Yangtze River, China's longest, have started to pay
off.
</P>
<P>
Information from the Gezhouba Hydropower Plant, located on the
middle reaches of the river, shows that the trash which piled up
before pollution controls were instituted has been decreasing by
one third since the flood season began this summer, falling by two
m.
</P>
<P>
The hydropower plant serves as a benchmark for trash pollution
on the Yangtze. Previously, whenever the summer flood season began
the large amount of flotage from the upper reaches of the river
collected at the infall of the power plant or got stuck against
the pollution fencing of the power plant. The height of the trash
heap amounted to four m on the most serious occasions.
</P>
<P>
The large trash heap affected the power generation of the plant,
which had to stop production 18 times in 1998 in order to clear
the trash.
</P>
<P>
Cities along the Yangtze have stepped up the management of
trash from human activities and banned random dumping on both
banks of the river since last year's record floods.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing Municipality, for instance, has cleared away its
riverside trash heap which had piled up over many years. In the
meantime, the navigation and port supervision authorities have
intensified the management and disposal of garbage created by
river vessels.
</P>
<P>
Now, all in-bound vessels must obtain trash disposal
certificates issued by professional trash collection organizations,
otherwise they will not be allowed to leave the river ports.
</P>
<P>
Riverside cities like Yichang, where the Gezhouba hydropower
plant is located, have increased the number of boats allocated to
rubbish collection, and activities under such slogans as "Purify
the water of the Yangtze and protect the mother river" are being
held to improve people's awareness of environmental protection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
