<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Forces in Congo Not Likely to Return by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean forces based in the
 Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) are not likely to return
home before the end of the year as expected, commander of the
Allied Forces Major general Anthony Chingombe has said.
</P>
<P>
The commander told the Zimbabwe News Agency in Kinshasa Friday
that this was mainly because of the continued violation of the
July 10 Lusaka ceasefire agreement by rebels and their backers.
</P>
<P>
"Although the ceasefire is in effect in some parts of the
country, some rebels and their allies are violating it," the
Zimbabwe News Agency Saturday quoted Chingombe as saying.
</P>
<P>
"With such a situation continuing the Zimbabwean troops as well
as those of Namibia and Angola cannot simply leave the situation
like that," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, said the commander, the situation was at a standstill
in the eastern front of the vast central African country.
</P>
<P>
He said recent violations were carried out at Makanza and
Bangadeya more than 1,000 km from Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
"Even if Jean-Perre Bemba of the Movement of the Liberation of
Congo signed the agreement on Monday, we cannot take him seriously
because it is his troops that are continuing with violations in
the northern front," he said.
</P>
<P>
The other rebel group, the Congolese Restoration of Democracy
(RCD), did not sign because of the leadership wrangle between
Emile Ilunga and Ernest Wamba dia Wamba.
</P>
<P>
On the rebels who were surrendering, Chingombe said Congolese
President Laurent Kabila was prepared to approach non-governmental
organizations to help with their rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
So far 900 rebels had surrendered and there were indications
that more would follow suit, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the joint military commission whose task would be to monitor
the ceasefire agreement, he said, it was still to be commissioned
by ministers of defense who had forces in the Congo.
</P>
<P>
"The ceasefire is going to hold if the masters of the rebels,
Rwanda and Uganda, respect it," Chingombe said, adding that Rwanda
had three brigades involved in the Congolese war while Uganda had
two brigades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
