<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Lagos State's new Police
Commissioner Mike Okiro who assumed duty Friday in Nigeria's
economic hub has pledged to use " orthodox or unorthodox" ways to
beat the surging crimes in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
Okiro, who was deployed from Benue State to take over from
former Commissioner of Police Sunday Agbedo, said: "Lagos is not
new to me, it is only the command that is new. I have only been
away from Lagos for about four or five years," the Guardian
newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
While calling for the cooperation of the people for the success
of his assignment, he said he would run an open door policy.
</P>
<P>
Lagos state, which hosts the country's largest city with the
same name, had seen more than one thousand murders in the past
decade only, according to official record released recently.
</P>
<P>
Okiro, who joined the police force as Cadet Assistant
Superintendent of Police (ASP) on August 1, 1977, promised to turn
things around in the combat against crime in the state."
</P>
<P>
"I promise that there would be improvement in the state, he
vowed. "To curb crime wave in the state and unravel the
circumstances behind the recent attacks on prominent persons in
the state, and to bring to book all that are proved to be guilty
are my major priorities." 
