<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Quicken Steps of Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government is
committed to prompt completion of the on-going privatization so as
to enable it to concentrate efforts on other aspects of
governance, Vice-President Atiku Abubakar has said in capital
Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The activities of government were usually slowed down when
distracted by issues meant for the private sector, Atiku said
Friday when addressing the House of Representative's Committee on
Privatization, The Guardian newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Once privatization was concluded, he said, the government would
devote its attention to governance, maintenance of law and order,
ensuring social equity and fairness in order to foster sense of
belonging among citizens.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president explained that privatization involved
fundamental changes in the roles of the state and the private
sector. While the private sector acts as the fulcrum for economic
growth, the government plays the role of a catalyst by providing
the enabling environment, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also informed the legislators that many of the government
agencies earmarked for privatization have suffered from misuse of
their monopoly powers, defective capital base, undue bureaucracy
and colossal mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
The government would be the ultimate umpire in the
privatization effort, said Atiku, but he assured that the hallmark
of the exercise would be openness, transparency and
accountability.
</P>
<P>
A.E. Amadi, chairman of the committee, pledged that members of
the body would properly assess and evaluate public enterprises to
be privatized and commercialized and ensure that shares were not
sold to a few private hands to avoid monopoly.
</P>
<P>
He said the 30-man committee would make decisions on all
matters relating to privatization and commercialization of
government agencies, monitor the functions and operations of such
agencies as well as consider their yearly budgets.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the efficient handling of the responsibility, Amadi
said that sub-committees on petroleum, industry, transport,
communication, finance, insurance and banking, as well as power,
steel and mining, had been established by the House of
Representatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
