<DOCNO> XIE19990807.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Passes Legislation on Free Legal Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Legal workers in the south
China province of Guangdong will have their work permits revoked
for periods ranging from three months to one year if they fail to
perform their duty of offering free legal aid as requested.
</P>
<P>
This is laid down in the document "Legal Aid Regulations of
Guangdong Province", which was adopted by the Standing Committee
of the Guangdong Provincial People's Congress early this month.
The regulation, the first of its kind in China, will be effective
as of September 1.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulations, lawyers, notaries and grass-roots
legal workers are required to offer free legal aid as requested by
courts or other relevant organizations to destitute or handicapped
people, juveniles, defendants facing the death penalty and who are
not represented by lawyers, and social welfare organizations in
need of legal help.
</P>
<P>
Foreign suspects, stateless persons, and unrepresented
defendants may apply for free legal aid from the concerned courts
or other relevant organizations during the process of litigation
and investigation.
</P>
<P>
Persons who obtain free legal aid by unlawful means will be
deprived of such aid, and will be forced to pay legal service
charges, according to the regulations.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong, which is in the forefront of China's reform and
opening-up drive, led the nation by setting up the first legal aid
center in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
Since then, some 30 branches of the center have been
established across the province. In 1997 alone, these
organizations handled 24,000 cases involving free legal aid. In
the same period, the local legal organizations have received 4,300
letters and personal requests for legal aid from 20,000 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990807.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Rebel Leader Intervenes to Free Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August (Xinhua) -- S. Leone's former rebel leader Foday
Sankoh has said in Togo's capital Lome that he had ordered a group
of former junta soldiers to free the hostages held by rebel
faction loyal to Johnny Koromah.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not worried," he said. "The position of the high command
is that this has no effect on the peace accord," said the leader
of the Revolutionary United Front(RUF) on Friday.
</P>
<P>
About 30 U.N. employees, aid workers, west African intervention
force soldiers and journalists are currently held in the Okra
Hills, some 65 km outside Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The RUF leader said the kidnapping was an "isolated" incident
that did not signal a broader split in the rebels' alliance with
Sierra Leone's former military junta and noted that he had ordered
the soldiers to release their captives.
</P>
<P>
He also accused officials of United Nations and West African
Peacekeeping Force, ECOMOG, of carelessly provoking the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said they had failed to contact senior rebel officials
before sending the delegation into rebel-held territory.
</P>
<P>
The kidnap took place when an international delegation met with
junta soldiers, who had said they would free about 150 women and
children captured during the war.
</P>
<P>
The junta soldiers freed several captives Thursday, which
included two U. N. officials, a Reuters reporter and a clergy man,
requiring them to convey their demand for food, medicine among
others.
</P>
<P>
The hostages freed Thursday night said they had been held in
the village of Magbini, about 55 miles east of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
They also demand the freedom for their leader Koroma believed
to be detained by the RUF. Koroma and his men fought the
country's head of state and allied itself with the RUF rebels in
1997, but was 10 months latter flushed out by the Nigeria-led
ECOMOG force backing the unseated President Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
However Sankoh denied Koroma was detained, insisting he was the
"number two man" in the rebel alliance.
</P>
<P>
Relations between rebel commanders and former junta soldiers
remain murky. The groups theoretically are allied. But many former
junta soldiers felt excluded when the rebels signed the peace
accord on July 7 in Lome.
</P>
<P>
Koroma led a May 1997 coup that ousted the government of
President Kabbah and then Koroma's junta. 
</P>
</TEXT>
