<HEADLINE> China Secures Women's Singles Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 6 (Xinhua) -- World No. 1 ranked
player Wang Nan eliminated South Korean Ryu Ji Hye on Saturday,
making the women's singles final an all-Chinese affair at the world
table tennis championships.
</P>
<P>
World Cup holder Wang Nan, who led the Chinese team after
multi-world champion Deng Yaping opted out of the championships to
concentrate on her studies in Britain's Nottingham University, beat
Ryu 22-24, 21-8, 21-15, 16-21, 21-16.
</P>
<P>
"I am sort of lucky to survive," said Wang. "Ryu has never played
so well."
</P>
<P>
Wang had a record of 11 wins and 4 losses against the South Korean,
including eight straight wins since July 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the deciding set, Wang came from 1-6 down to edge ahead with
wide-angled topspin strokes while Rye looked nervous and didn't move
as quickly as she does.
</P>
<P>
"I had chance but I didn't hold on," said Rye.
</P>
<P>
In the all-Chinese semifinal, 17-year-old Li Nan, who had upset No.
4 seed Qianhong Gotsch of Germany and No. 2 seed Li Ju of China,
went down to Zhang Yining, 18-21, 21-10, 21-15, 19-21, 21-16.
</P>
