<HEADLINE> ORBIS Flying Eye Hospital Holds Public Relations in Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The ORBIS aircraft, the world's
only flying eye hospital, arrived in Macao on Friday for public
relations following sight-saving programs in China's Urumqi and
Lanzhou cities.
</P>
<P>
ORBIS is a non-profit, humanitarian organization dedicated to
fighting avoidable blindness worldwide. In the mid-1970s, Dr.
David Paton, an ophthalmologist from Texas of the United States,
conceived the idea of an airborne ophthalmologic treating and
teaching hospital.
</P>
<P>
With a Douglas DC-8 plane presented by the United Airlines and
other donations from enthusiastic people, the ORBIS aircraft took
flight in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Expenses of ORBIS operations come from donations from
individuals, companies and organizations, and ophthalmologic
specialists and other medical persons work voluntarily to large
extent.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the ORBIS hospital has visited 79 countries and
conducted 393 medical programs, training more than 46,000 doctors
and nurses in sight-saving skills. It is estimated that millions
of people suffering from eye diseases have benefited directly or
indirectly from ORBIS.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, ORBIS has conducted 67 medical programs in
China's 21 provincial areas and trained 12,700 doctors and nurses.
</P>
<P>
The ORBIS aircraft will leave for Taiwan on Monday for similar
public relations and then head for the Philippines, Myanmar and
Bangladesh for medical programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990807.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: BJP to Emerge as Single Largest Party in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The BJP could emerge as the
single largest party in the next Lok Sabha with more than 200
seats, says an opinion poll conducted by Outlook weekly and the
Center for Media Studies.
</P>
<P>
The opinion poll, which will be released on Sunday, covered
10,650 voters between July 25 and 30 in 71 constituencies in 16
states. It predicts 279 to 289 seats for the Bharatiya Janata
Party and its allies.
</P>
<P>
The Congress and its allies come a distant second with 152 to
162 seats.
</P>
<P>
A loose "Third Front" comprising the four left parties, the
Samajwadi Party, the TMC, the BSP and the AGP is projected to bag
between 63 and 68 seats. Others, including the TDP, the
Nationalist Congress Party and four small parties, could win
between 34 and 39 seats.
</P>
<P>
If the survey's projections turn out right, for the first time
in India, the BJP could overtake the Congress as the single
largest party in terms of votes polled at 27.5 percent (up 2
percent from last time) compared to the Congress, which dropped to
23.85 percent (down 2 percent).
</P>
<P>
The opinion poll suggests that had Sharad Pawar remained in the
Congress, a hung Lok Sabha again could have been expected.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-one percent of those polled felt that Prime minister
Vajpayee is the best bet to lead the country.
</P>
<P>
The BJP and allies are set to poll 39.15 percent of the votes
compared to 37.2 percent in 1998, a swing of 1.95 percent in their
favor.
</P>
<P>
The Congress and allies are projected by the opinion poll to
get 31.15 percent of the votes share, a rise of 1.49 percent since
1998 when the party polled 29.66 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
The biggest blow in terms of votes share will be the Third
Front: 17.53 percent in 1999 compared to 21.93 percent in 1998,
showing a negative 4.4 swing against it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
