<HEADLINE> UAE Achieves Major Progress in Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The number of government
schools in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) has risen to 687 this
year from just 39 in 1966, indicating that the Gulf country has
made great progress in education.
</P>
<P>
The schools are now offering a high standard of education to
some 400,000 students, the Khaleej Times daily Saturday quoted a
report from the Ministry of Education as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the education process of the country had
witnessed significant developments since 1966, when President
Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nayhan, became ruler of Abu Dhabi, the
largest of the seven emirates which formed the federation in 1971.
</P>
<P>
Today, in the seven emirates comprising Abu Dhabi, Dubai,
Sharjah, Ajman, Fujairah, Umm Al Quwain and Ras Al Khaimah, there
is a teacher for every 18 students in kindergartens, one for
every 16 students at the primary level and one teacher for every
11 students at preparatory and secondary levels, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"This teacher-student ratio is very high, even when compared
to developed countries," it added.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, plans are afoot now to introduce
fundamental changes in the education process to keep pace with
the development requirements of the next millenium.
</P>
<P>
"Our strategy will be based on a positive participation of all
sections of the community in creating a developed education
system and implementing education programs, because continuous
training programs are the main tool in promoting skills of the
manpower in today's world," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
