<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Loses Grip on Food Security as Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe, as the bread basket of
southern Africa, is gradually losing its top spot of food
self-sufficiency with food imports almost doubling from 2.3
percent in 1990 to 4.5 percent of its total consumption last year.
</P>
<P>
The Herald daily Saturday quoted economic highlights of the
Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe as saying that accelerated implementation
of drought mitigation measures and the maintenance of viable
agricultural policies would go a long way in containing the food
imports, saving on the limited foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
"If the economy does not generate sufficient foreign currency
to meet import requirements, there will be pressure on the
exchange rate," said the bank.
</P>
<P>
It said the trade liberation program introduced in 1991 had
contributed to a significant increase in imports. 
</P>
