<HEADLINE> 600 Somali Refugees to Be Relocated in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Over 600 Somali refugees who have
been living at St. Annes Camp with the Mombasa Central Business
District in Kenya's southeastern Coast Province have been
registered for relocation in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), the
refugees started registering Friday after the Kenyan government
announced it would close down the camp by the weekend, the East
African Standard newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
However, the fate of some 1,800 refugees remains unknown. They
had refused to register with the UNHCR as directed by Mombasa
District Commissioner Wilfred Legei.
</P>
<P>
It is said the 600 registered refugees are scheduled to be
relocated to the Kakuma camp in Rift Valley Province and the
Dadaab camp in North Eastern Province this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Early this week, Legei ordered the closure of the camp and
directed all refugees be relocated to North Eastern Province, and
also took the issue with a local businessman who has issued the
refugees with national identification cards illegally.
</P>
<P>
Legei said the government was investigating the matter and
will take action against the businessman who has housed the
refugees since they arrived in Kenya over eight years ago.
</P>
