<DOCNO> XIE19990807.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Researchers: Bottled Water May Contaminate Contact Lenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Rinsing contact lenses with
bottled water may contaminate them and put contact lens wearers at
risk for eye infections, the American Academy of Ophthalmology (
AAO) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
A study appearing in the August issue of Ophthalmology, AAO's
clinical journal, showed that some brands of bottled water contain
considerable amounts of bacteria and other microorganism,
including an organism normally found in the human urinary tract.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at the Baylor College of Medicine in Houston, the
United States, analyzed 23 different brands of locally available,
non-carbonated bottled water. Nearly half of them contained living
microorganisms, including bacteria, yeast, mold and algae.
</P>
<P>
AAO said that microorganisms known to cause contact lens-
related bacterial keratitis were found in some of the bottled
water samples tested in the Baylor study. Sterile contact lenses
became contaminated in as little as one minute after being exposed
to the water samples.
</P>
<P>
While microorganisms can come from natural sources, AAO said
that much of the contamination occurs during the manufacturing
process.
</P>
<P>
To avoid the risk of infection, AAO recommends that only
sterile solutions be used for rinsing contact lenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
