<HEADLINE> Third Round of World Chess Championship Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Michael Krasenkow of Poland
was the only top seed to run into deep trouble Friday in the first
game of the third round of the World Chess Championship in Las
Vegas on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Vadim Zvjaginsev of Russia defeated the eighth-seeded Krasenkow
with the black pieces. Now the Polish grandmaster must win with
black in the second game of the round Saturday or go home.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-two of the original 100 players remain in the running
for the seven-round knockout tournament. It will run through the
month.
</P>
<P>
Favorites who won with black were England's Nigel Short over
Alexander Beliavsky of Slovenia and Alexei Fedorov of Belarus over
Jan Timman of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Three of the top seeds won with white Friday.
</P>
<P>
Alexei Shirov of Spain, the second seed, beat Gilbert Milos of
Brazil in a very tough fight.
</P>
<P>
Sixth-seed Vassily Ivanchuk of the Ukraine won over the tough
Sergei Shipov of Russia.
</P>
<P>
Veselin Topolov of Bulgaria scored a quick win off Lev Psakhis
of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria's veteran Kiril Georgiev pulled a mild upset, using
the white pieces to best the seventh seed, Peter Svidler of Russia.
</P>
<P>
Top-seeded Boris Gelfand of Israel was held to a draw the 68
year-old Viktor Korchnoi of Switzerland. Korchnoi played matches
for the world title against Karpov in 1978 and 1981. Karpov won
both matches.
</P>
<P>
Judit Polgar, the strongest woman player in the world, drew
easily with black against Jordi Magem Badals of Spain. 
</P>
