<HEADLINE> Philippines Allows Small Savers to Invest in T-Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Saturday that it has raised more than 50 million pesos (1.3
million U.S. dollars) in Treasury bills sold to small investors to
generate funds for its pro-poor development programs.
</P>
<P>
These investments in risk-free government securities came in
the form of T-Bill placements in denominations of 5,000 pesos (130
dollars) to 25,000 pesos (650 dollars), said the presidential
office in a report issued here.
</P>
<P>
As of May 31, it said, the Bureau of Treasury has sold 50
million pesos (1.3 million dollars) worth of T-Bills to small
savers like teachers, ordinary office workers, housewives and
retirees.
</P>
<P>
T-Bills used to be available only in large denominations
ranging from 100,000 pesos (2,590 dollars) and 10 million pesos
(259,000 dollars), and therefore, accessible only to banks,
pension funds and other big investors.
</P>
<P>
The small denomination T-Bills under the Small Investors'
Program (SIP) are available through the state-owned Land Bank and
Development Bank of the Philippines, the office said.
</P>
<P>
First launched in Manila in January, the SIP started with a
minimum denomination of 25,000 pesos (650 dollars). This was
further reduced to 5,000 pesos (130 dollars) to allow more small
investors to participate in the program.
</P>
<P>
The program was gradually expanded to major cities, including
Cebu, Iloilo and Davao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
