<HEADLINE> Kenya Launches Special Crime Prevention Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has launched a special
crime prevention police unit to curb the influx and trafficking
of illegal arms in a wake of increasing case of carjackings at
gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
At the inauguration of the unit Friday at Kitengela not far
from the capital Nairobi, Kenyan Police Commissioner Philemon
Abong'o said one of the team's prime duties was to identify the
sources and conduits of illegal firearms.
</P>
<P>
Media reports here Saturday quoted Abong'o as saying despite
strict gun- control legislation in this country, illegal firearms
smuggled from the neighboring war-torn countries continued to end
up in the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
He noted that some refugees to whom Kenya has offered
hospitality have been involved in smuggling illegal weapons into
the country.
</P>
<P>
The new unit will take strategic positions and search every
motor vehicles, vessel and craft entering the Kenyan borders and
also suspect vehicles on the road.
</P>
<P>
According to the police commissioner, the special squad draws
officers from the General Service Unit, regular police, Criminal
Investigations Department, traffic police and the dog unit.
</P>
<P>
They are equipped with adequate transport and state-of-the-art
 communications equipment and other gadgets to enable them locate
concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, violent crime is on the increase in Kenya,
especially carjackings in capital Nairobi. Earlier reports said
that in Nairobi, there were an estimated 5,000 pieces of illegal
arms in the hands of criminals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
