<HEADLINE> Vietnam Intensifies Efforts on Poverty Eradication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is intensifying its efforts
on hunger alleviation and poverty reduction by striving to help
some 300,000 poor households escape hunger this year.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has planned to reduce the rate of poverty-stricken
households nationwide to 13.7 percent this year, Vietnam News
Agency Saturday quoted Vietnam's Ministry of Labor, War Invalids
and Social Affairs as saying.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam now has 2.4 million households classified as poor,
accounting for 15.7 percent of the total population. There are
almost 1,500 poor communes nationwide each with more than 40
percent of their households classified as in poverty.
</P>
<P>
Hunger and poverty eradication has been set as a major policy
and an important undertaking by the Vietnamese government. The
hunger alleviation and poverty reduction program started in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government planned to allocate 900 billion
Vietnamese dong (VND) (64.3 million U.S. dollars) to the national
program on hunger elimination and poverty reduction this year with
70 percent being channeled to the 1,000 poorest communes
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The government also planned to invest most of the more than
4,000 billion VND (290 million U.S. dollars) raised from the
recent State bond sales in poverty eradication activities.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnam's national program on hunger alleviation and
poverty reduction aims to bring down the rate of poor households
to below 10 percent next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
