<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 08:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dead Sea Shrinking At Alarming Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Dead Sea, the saltiest body of
water on earth and world-renowned tourist resort, is shrinking at
an alarming rate and might disappear in 20-25 years, Jordan
Times reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Landlocked in the Jordan Valley between Israel and Jordan, the
Dead Sea has shrunk to around 50 kilometers in length from 80
kilometers three decades ago due to drought, pollution and over
exploitation, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Some 90 percent of the Jordan river water, is now being
diverted into Jordan and Israel after the two countries signed a
peace treaty in 1994, and the river water's quality has
deteriorated due to agricultural run-offs and increased salinity.
</P>
<P>
Water fountains around the sea are also dammed to gather water
for agricultural purposes, while other fountains were polluted,
Jordan Times said.
</P>
<P>
Industrial activities around the Dead Sea's banks also
contributed to the problems, massive evaporation pools vaporize
the sea's water to extract minerals and for manufacturing beauty
products.
</P>
<P>
Environmental impacts on the Dead Sea also include air
pollution caused by dust and fuel burning, and disposal of
hazardous materials, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Due to these factors, the Dead Sea might disappear in 20-25
years, warned Dureid Mahasneh, former general secretary of the
Jordan Valley Authority of the desert kingdom.
</P>
<P>
He said the Dead Sea's water level drops by 10 to 15
centimeters every year in modern history.
</P>
<P>
Each year, millions of tourists from all over the world are
flocking to its shores to float on its water, which contains high
level of sulphur.
</P>
<P>
The thick black mud around the sea's shores are also found to
have healing effects believed to treat various skin diseases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990807.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Press Cautioned Against Exposure of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The (Olusegun) Obasanjo Leadership
Forum, a none governmental organization in Nigeria, has urged the
media to exercise caution in the performance of its duties as it
relates to the exposure of corrupt officials.
</P>
<P>
The forum noted in a statement the embarrassing revelations and
 allegations bordering on the integrity of public office holders
and pleaded that "the media should not send out wrong signals to
other forces contending for political power through means other
than the ballot box," the Guardian newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement acknowledged that "the media owes it a
duty to hold public office holders accountable, but the
dissipation of energy on allegations of misconduct against
members of the legislature has become costly distraction which the
nation can ill-afford."
</P>
<P>
The forum also called on "public officers who have skeletons in
their cupboards should follow the path of honor by resigning
their appointments or membership of any of the arms of government
instead of waiting to be disgraced publicly".
</P>
<P>
It appealed to those "who shun out these allegations to be sure
of their facts before publishing to ensure that precious time is
not wasted investigating nothing and the press and the
legislature must thread cautiously in their utterances and
statements to ensure that our fragile democracy is not
endangered."
</P>
<P>
Nigerian news media has successfully pulled down the country's
House Speaker Alhaji Buhari in a campaign spear-headed by the
Lagos- based weekly The News and is engaging a battle with the
Senator Speaker Evan Enwerem by accusing him of trying to cover
his past conviction.
</P>
<P>
While the role of the press in the anti-corruption battle is
generally praised, there are people who caution that the press
should not go to the extreme in the find-the-skeleton fever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
