<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Masood Forces Close in on Taliban-Held Districts: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The anti-Taliban Northern
Alliance forces are closing in on the Taliban-held districts of
Tagab and Nejrab, northeast of capital Kabul.
</P>
<P>
A report from Kabul quoted an opposition spokesman as saying
Saturday that the forces loyal to former defense minister Ahmad
Shah Masood were confident to reoccupy the two districts.
</P>
<P>
There was sporadic fighting in the area overnight, said the
report. The Taliban fighter jets had carried out four sorties on
Panjsher Valley, the opposition's last stronghold, it added.
</P>
<P>
"There were civilians killed in the bombing raids but we're
still assessing the damage," the spokesman was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban launched their long-awaited summer offensive on
July 28 on Tagab and took the nearby city of Nejrab quickly. Over
the next week the Taliban forces scored major victories and forced
the opposition forces to retreat.
</P>
<P>
But the opposition led by Masood launched a counter attack on
Thursday and pushed the front line back to within 30 kilometers
north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that between 800 and 1,000 Taliban fighters
were killed in the counter offensive. However, casualty figures
from the opposition side were not immediately available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
