<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian PM Urges Normalizing Situation in Dagestan Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin on Saturday ordered the armed forces chief of staff and
the Interior Ministry forces chief to normalize the situation in
the Dagestan republic, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The order came amid reports that about 500 armed Chechen
militants infiltrated into Dagestan early Saturday and trenched
near the villages of Ansalta and Rakhata in the mountainous
Botlikhsky district.
</P>
<P>
The armed Chechen group is believed to include Arabs and
people from Central Asia, Tass quoted the Dagestani interior
ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is moving its forces to the Botlikhsky district
and ascertaining intents of the Chechen guerrillas, Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
Recent weeks have witnessed a number of skirmishes along the
borders between Dagestan and the neighboring republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
At least 14 people were killed in shoot-outs between heavily
armed gangs and Russian security forces near the border on Monday
and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Russian officials said earlier that the attackers were based
in Chechnya and get into Russia through the mountains.
</P>
<P>
Since then, as many as 150 fighters have occupied a Dagestani
village near the border.
</P>
<P>
Russia sent additional troops and military equipment to the
region Wednesday, saying it wants to guard against potential
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Kidnappings and violence have plagued Chechnya and neighboring
regions in recent years. According to the Russian Interior
Ministry, 1,094 people have been abducted since January 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In another sign of anarchy reigning the area, a band of
kidnappers has demanded 7 million U.S. dollars for the release of
Gennady Shpigun, the Russian Interior Ministry's envoy to Chechnya
who has been held hostage for several months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
