<DOCNO> XIE19990807.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Increase Calamity Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Social Security System (SSS)
in the Philippines announced Saturday that it will ease its
requirements for calamity loans to help members who have been
affected by the recent floods.
</P>
<P>
SSS President Carlos Arellano told reporters here that the
management has submitted a recommendation to the Social Security
Commission, the institution's policy-making body, to increase the
loan ceiling from 5,000 pesos (129 U.S. dollars) to 8,000 pesos
(207 dollars) and reduce the contribution requirement from 36 to
24 months.
</P>
<P>
"Our members, who have been affected by the floods, face an
emergency. They need all the help they can get," Arellano said.
</P>
<P>
The SSS, the country's major social security body for private
workers, opened this week its calamity loan portfolio after
floods, caused by monsoon rains, submerged large areas in Metro
Manila and the provinces of Rizal, Pampanga and Pangasinan.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 people were killed and thousands fled their homes
as flood waters surged through the low-lying areas. Millions of
pesos worth of crops and properties were destroyed in the disaster
areas.
</P>
<P>
Arellano said members who have existing calamity loans of not
more than 10,000 pesos (259 dollars) would qualify for the new
portfolio as soon as it will be approved by the commission.
</P>
<P>
Since 1981, the SSS has granted 6.15 billion pesos (159 million
dollars) of calamity loans to its members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
