<DOCNO> XIE19990807.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Shrimp Sector Fails to Reach Export Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's fledging shrimp
sector, which had kept the country's export turnover healthy over
the last couple of years, failed to attain the export target for
the last fiscal year ending on June 30, according to the latest
statistics of the Bangladesh Frozen Food Exporters' Association
(BFFEA) released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh earned about 247.32 million U.S. dollars by
exporting some 58.33 million pounds of frozen food (mainly shrimp)
in the last fiscal year against the target of 350 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The BFFEA attributed the shortfall to escalating production
costs due to up-gradation of processing plants and abrupt falls in
shrimp prices in the international market.
</P>
<P>
Prices of frozen food experienced a decline of about 25-40
percent in the international market in recent days as most of the
South Asian countries are dumping their products at throw-away
prices due to massive devaluation of their currencies.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi seafood is facing still competition in the
international market, especially from Latin America. The share of
Bangladesh in the international frozen food market is less than
two percent against the combined total of nearly 20 percent by
India, Thailand and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The South Asian country has the capacity to meet five percent
of the international demand if exporters are backed by proper
policy support from the government, shrimp exporters said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
