<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sun Protection Defenses Skin Cancer Best, Researchers Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 6 (Xinhua) -- An influential U.S. medical
association said Friday that sun protection is still the key to
skin cancer prevention, despite new research that shed light on
how the body protects itself from the disease.
</P>
<P>
In a study published in the August 6 issue of Science,
researchers at the Texas University detailed apoptosis, the body's
recently identified line of defense against skin cancer. During
apoptosis, damaging sunlight exposures may activate the body's
natural defense mechanism and act to kill the cells with the
irreparably damaged DNA that may otherwise become skin cancers.
</P>
<P>
"These are exciting developments, but it is crucial that
individuals do not rely solely on their natural defense mechanisms
to prevent skin cancer," said the American Academy of Dermatology
(AAD).
</P>
<P>
The human body's defenses have limits and cannot repair all of
the DNA damage, said AAD, arguing that otherwise no one would ever
die of skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
AAD also quoted dermatologist Mark Naylor at University of
Oklahoma as saying that while some individuals have interpreted
this study to mean that a sunburn may actually stop the beginning
of skin cancer, in fact, sunburn is the primary cause of DNA
damage in the first place. "There is an overwhelming body of data
which demonstrates that a sunburn is the leading cause of melanoma,
the deadliest form of skin cancer," said the expert.
</P>
<P>
According to AAD, skin cancer is the most common form of cancer
in the United States, with about 1 million new cases diagnosed
each year. It is estimated that 44,200 will be diagnosed with
melanoma in 1999, a 6 percent increase from 1998. And
approximately 7,300 deaths will be attributed to melanoma in 1999.
</P>
<P>
To prevent skin cancer, AAD recommends that individuals adopt a
comprehensive sun protection program that includes wearing sun
protective clothing, avoiding the sun between 10:00 a.m. and 4:00
p.m., seeking shade whenever possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
