<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
Most newspapers report on the frontpage that Chinese President
Jiang Zemin yesterday told visiting United Nations Development
Program Administrator Mark Brown that the role of United Nations
organizations should be increased to help realize the
comprehensive economic and social development of developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also told the UNDP official that China is willing to
continue and strengthen its cooperation with the UN and its
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The newspapers also report that China's state-owned assets
amounted to 8.22 trillion yuan ( 993 billion U.S. dollars) at the
end of 1998, surging 13.8 percent year-on-year, according to the
Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
People's Daily
</P>
<P>
--The newspaper published its third commentary, entitled "
Instigating Protection of Falun Gong Is Seeking Confrontation", to
continue to expose the true nature and harm of Falun Gong.
</P>
<P>
--The Office for Cultural and Ethical Progress with the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) yesterday convened
a forum calling for greater efforts in exposing and criticizing
Falun Gong and stepping up construction of cultural and ethical
progress.
</P>
<P>
--Scientists with the Shanghai Cellular Biology Institute of
the Chinese Academy of Sciences have successfully built a cDNA
array, the primary form to a biological chip that contains 8,600
different human genes.
</P>
<P>
 Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
--Three nonferrous metal groups, originally separate entities
under the China Nonferrous Metal Industry Corporation (CNIC),
announced their establishment in Beijing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The three groups are the China Aluminum Corporation (Chalco),
the China Copper Lead Zinc Corporation (CCLZ), and the China Rare
Metals and Rare Earth (Group) Corporation (CRRC).
</P>
<P>
--The newspaper today also carried a special Xinhua News Agency
commentary stressing that the real nature of Lee Teng-hui's "
special state-to-state relations" statement is splittism.
</P>
<P>
It says the written speech of Koo Chenfu, chairman of the
Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) on July 30 and the written
explanation of the "Mainland Affairs Council" on August 1 were
attempts to whitewash Lee Teng-hui's "two states" statement.
</P>
<P>
China Daily
</P>
<P>
--Large-scale construction of water control facilities since
last summer has apparently paid off as the number of emergencies
along river banks has declined substantially this year, despite
flooding being almost as serious as last year, officials say.
</P>
<P>
--Legal experts said yesterday that the separatist remarks of
Taiwan's Lee Teng-hui do not hold water in the context of
international law.
</P>
<P>
--The State Family Planning Commission yesterday launched a
national campaign to reduce the number of babies with birth
defects. 
