<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. Timor's Voter Registration Closes With Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The 22-day voter registration for
the direct ballot in most areas of East Timor closed Friday with
more violence, reports reaching here Saturday from Dili, capital
of East Timor, said.
</P>
<P>
Despite requests to extend the registration period,
registration centers closed on Friday with 439,580 people
registered, 427,190 of whom live in East Timor, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
The registration period in 14 remote areas will conclude on
August 8, according to UN officials in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
However, sporadic violence colored the run-up to the ballot
planned for August 30, with the last incident revealed on Friday
by UN Mission in East Timor (UNAMET) spokesman Yasuhiro Ueki.
</P>
<P>
He said a UNAMET official was slightly wounded by a chunk of
concrete when some 20 pro-integration militias attacked a house in
Ainaro regency on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday at 2:30 p.m. a registration post at the state
Batugade high school was attacked by at least 50 militiamen. Two
other registration posts in the vicinity immediately closed.
</P>
<P>
Ueki also said Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas and
several other ministers are scheduled to arrive in Dili Saturday
to meet UNAMET to discuss various issues on the autonomy ballot.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, coordinator of the Commission of Peace and
Stability, BN Marbun, said the security situation ahead of the
ballot was improving.
</P>
<P>
According to schedule, the voter registration period would be
followed by a six-day documentation period (August 5-10), a 17-day
campaign period (August 11-27) and a two-day cooling-down period
(August 28-29).
</P>
<P>
The UN is organizing a direct ballot in East Timor to enable
the East Timorese to accept or reject a wide-ranging autonomy
offered by the Indonesian government early this year.
</P>
<P>
A rejection of the autonomy proposal will mean independence for
the former Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
East Timor was integrated into Indonesia in 1976 in a move
never recognized by the UN. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
