<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercosur Emergency Meeting Opens in Uruguay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Foreign and Economic Ministers
from the four countries of the Southern Common Market (Mercosur)
met here Friday to seek a solution to the trade disputes between
Argentina and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The Mercosur Council emergency meeting, initiated by Uruguayan
President Julio Sanguinetti, is expected to arrive at some
decisions to address the intra-zone trade distortion in the bloc
comprising Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay, following the
devaluation of Brazil's currency.
</P>
<P>
Brazil has gained a price advantage in its exports since it
devalued its currency, the real, by 30 percent in January. The
Mercosur, the third largest trade bloc in the world which yearly
produces 1 trillion U.S. dollars in goods and service for 200
million consumers, is facing its worst ever impasse after Brazil
forced Argentina to scrap import quotas on textiles and shoes two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
However, Uruguayan Foreign Minister Didier Opertti stressed on
Friday before the start of the meeting the confidence over the
bloc's prospect, saying that "the moments are difficult, but not
awful, Mercosur will survive."
</P>
<P>
Technical negotiators from the four Mercosur countries met
Thursday to solve the growing internal trade dispute, but did not
reach a consensus.
</P>
<P>
Argentina, Uruguay and Paraguay insisted on the creation of a
mechanism for the macroeconomics coordination and transitory and
temporary measures to change the trade imbalances in the region.
</P>
<P>
Argentina proposed that such a mechanism will permit the
countries to adopt corrective measures, such as additional tariffs
or temporary quotas among the Mercosur partners.
</P>
<P>
However, Brazil opposed any kind of hindrance to the access of
its products to the markets, saying that no protectionist measures
can be applied in Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
Trade within Mercosur countries reached 15 billion dollars in
1998. But Argentina's exports, almost all of which go to Brazil,
fell by 27 percent in the first five months this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990807.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru, Bolivia Urged to Attend Andean Meeting to Boost Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- General Secretary of the Andean
Nations Community (CAN) Sebastian Alegrett on Friday urged Bolivia
and Peru to attend a meeting scheduled for August 13 in Lima to
accelerate the regional integration process.
</P>
<P>
Alegrett said that it is necessary to first realize trade
integration for the adoption of a single currency between the CAN
and the Southern Common Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, composed of Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay and Paraguay,
and CAN agreed on April 16, 1998, to gradually eliminate tariffs
and complete the construction of the free trade zone in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Lima meeting will discuss the Common External Tariffs to
perfect the Andean Customs Union.
</P>
<P>
The tariff structures of Bolivia and Peru are different from
Colombia, Ecuador, and Venezuela, the other members of the Andean
bloc.
</P>
<P>
The temporary suspension of Peru in the Program of Tariff
Liberation and of the Common External Tariff during 1992, and its
return later to the bloc caused the definition of a different
tariff structure.
</P>
<P>
Bolivia maintains margins of tariff preference because of its
geographical position and the economy asymmetry existing with the
rest of the CAN member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
