<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gene Discovery Promises Better Understanding of Sleep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists have found a
gene that causes narcolepsy in dogs, which will help tell how and
why humans sleep, the U.S. National Sleep Foundation (NSF) said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at Stanford University recently identified in dogs
the gene that causes narcolepsy, a chronic, potentially disabling
neurological disorder that causes excessive daytime sleepiness,
involuntary "sleep attacks," and loss of muscle control for many
people, an estimated 200,000 in the United States alone.
</P>
<P>
The NSF said it is believed that narcolepsy is as prevalent in
the United States as Parkinson's disease and multiple sclerosis,
but only one in four narcoleptics are diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
"Because this serious sleep disorder lies at the core of how
the brain signals us to sleep and to stay alert," NSF said of the
discovery, "this breakthrough will greatly advance scientists'
understanding of sleep in general, and will likely lead to
widespread applications for sleep problems other than narcolepsy."
</P>
<P>
The NSF is a nonprofit organization devoted to promoting public
understanding of sleep and sleep disorders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
