<HEADLINE> Highlights of Diplomatic News Weekly (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China expresses its regret over the escalation of the internal
conflict in Afghanistan, Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Zhu
Bangzao said.  He said that China sincerely hopes that the two
parties in the conflict pay attention to national and state
interest, cease fire as soon as possible, and seek a proper,
peaceful settlement of the Afghanistan issue through consultations
and negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Anti-China Bill Firmly Opposed
</P>
<P>
China strongly resents and firmly opposes a recent bill
submitted by a few U.S. congressmen in support of "one China, one
Taiwan" and "the independence of Taiwan," said Foreign Ministry
spokesman Zhu Bangzao.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that the Chinese side has already made a serious
representation with the U.S. government concerning the bill, and
has urged the U.S. to take concrete actions to prevent its passage.
</P>
<P>
"China demands that the U.S. congressmen immediately stop their
actions of interfering in China's internal affairs and infringing
upon China's sovereignty and territorial integrity," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu described the bill as "a serious infringement of China's
sovereignty and territorial integrity, a gross interference in
China's internal affairs, and an open provocation against all the
Chinese people."
</P>
<P>
A leading official of the Foreign Affairs Committee of China's
National People's Congress also strongly condemned and firmly
opposed the bill submitted by Sherrod Brown and some other members
of the U.S. House of Representatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
