<HEADLINE> Colombia Starts Substitution Plan to Cut Drug Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian
government and the United Nations International Drug Control
Program (UNIDCP) will start a substitution plan to cut illicit
drug crops in two departments of Colombia, a UNIDCP official said
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The plan, costing six million U.S. dollars, will halve the
cultivation area of drug crops in Meta and Caqueta departments,
which are located respectively in the northeast and southeast of
Colombia, said Klauss Nyholm, representative of the U.N. office.
</P>
<P>
The plan does not only aim to eradicate illicit cultivation of
crops such as coca and opium poppy, but also to boost economic
development by providing credit, constructing roads and other
infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
At least 5,000 peasants will benefit from the plan, said Nyholm.
</P>
<P>
The rebel Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC) has
said it is willing to cooperate in the implementation of the
project, said the official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
