<DOCNO> XIE19990807.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Maintains Momentum in Pan Am Pool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Joanne Malar
broke the Games record twice on Friday en route to her second gold
medal at the Pan Am Pool, winning the women's 200m medley race in
2:14.18 here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The home favourite raised the packed house to its feet as she
shattered her own record of 2:14.81, which was just set in the
morning's preliminaries, and added another gold to her 400m medley
title from August 2.
</P>
<P>
Martha Bowen of the United States was a distant second in 2:15.
26 and Malar's Canadian teammate M.L.Limpert third in 2:15.80.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 200m butterfly final, P.Pietucha of Canada failed
to improve his own record of 1:58.50, which was also established
in the morning's prelims on his way to the gold medal. His time
came as 1:59.10.
</P>
<P>
The American duo Steven Brown (1:59.52) and Devin Howard took
the silver and bronze respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 800m freestyle, American Kaitlin Sandeno rewrote
the Pan Am record to capture her second gold in the Winnipeg Games.
The newly-crowned 400m freestyle Pan Am champion lowered the old
mark of 8:34.72 to 8:34.65.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Fernando Scherer, who took out the men's 100m
freestyle two days ago, won in the 50m race today. But he failed
in his attempt to break his own best mark of 22.22 seconds, which
was set in the morning's heats, and had to settle for 22.24.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 100m backstroke, Cuba's Cabrera Falcon led
throughout to wrap up the race in 54.93 seconds, handily beating
off Brazilian Neto Massura (55.17) and American Matthew Allen (55.
86).
</P>
<P>
In today's last race women's 4X100 medley relay, the United
States went on a record-breaking trip, ripping more than two
seconds off the old mark to chalk up their seventh gold from the
swimming pool in 4:06.08. 
</P>
</TEXT>
