<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT August 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said on Friday he
will nominate Roger Ferguson to be vice chairman of the Federal
Reserve, the U.S. central bank.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson, 47, is currently serving as a member of the Fed board.
If confirmed by the Senate, he would replace Alice Rivlin, who
stepped down last month, and become the first black to serve as
vice chairman. (US-Fed-Nomination)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak promised on
Friday that Israel would start further implementation of the Wye
agreement within three weeks.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Television Channel One, Barak said
the timetable has been worked out with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser
Arafat last month. (Israel-Palestinians)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations announced Friday that it
will begin deploying international police monitors in Kosovo over
the weekend, with the first officers to be placed in Pristina,
where the crime rate is extremely high.
</P>
<P>
There are currently 474 out of an expected 3100 international
police in Kosovo with the mandate of enforcing law and order.
</P>
<P>
They are also charged with establishing and training a Kosovo
Police Service, a U.N. spokesman quoted the U.N. Police
Commissioner in Kosovo Sven Fredericksen as saying. (UN-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin is expected to sign "
a weighty package" during his official visit to Japan later this
year, the Foreign Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The package would include agreements on scientific and
technical cooperation, cultural ties and air traffic, the ministry
said in a statement released after the end of bilateral
consultations in Moscow, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Grigory Karasin and his
Japanese counterpart, Minoru Tamba, conducted the consultations. (
Russia-Japan-Consultations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton declared Friday that
the Republican bill of 792 billion dollars will not become law.
</P>
<P>
"This tax cut will not become law," he said, repeating his
determination to veto the bill.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he is willing to consider limited tax cuts using
projected budget surpluses, but only after Social Security and
Medicare are safeguarded for the future, public debt is paid down
and sufficient levels of spending are ensured for education,
defense environment protection and other programs. (US-Clinton-Tax
Cut) 
</P>
</TEXT>
