<HEADLINE> Chinese Courts to Stress Law-enforcement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 7 (Xinhua)-- China is to restructure its
higher people's courts, in a bid to provide people's courts with
greater law-enforcement capabilities, which have been reduced by
local protectionism.
</P>
<P>
Li Guoguang, vice-president of the Supreme People's Court,
announced the reform plan here today at a forum attended by
presidents of the country's higher people's courts.
</P>
<P>
Under the reform plan, higher people's courts are entitled to
command law-enforcement departments, which "is a major step in the
restructuring of the people's courts," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese courts have long been plagued by law-enforcement
difficulties resulting from local and professional protectionism.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June this year, more than 850,000 court rulings
were waiting to be executed, involving over 259 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, illegal interference and violent activities against
the enforcement of court rulings have been common phenomena across
the country.
</P>
<P>
Li stressed that courts at all levels should firmly combat
local protectionism, deal with those responsible in strict
accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that, while taking full advantage of the law-
enforcement powers enshrined in the law, people's courts
nationwide should attach the same importance to the protection of
national stability.
</P>
<P>
"Law-enforcement officers should never resort to
oversimplified and crude methods to enforce court rulings, but
improve their professional skills, so that the rights and interest
of the public can be better protected," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
