<HEADLINE> Schumacher Quick Return Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The hope for the immediate comeback
of Ferrari driver Michael Schumacher was snapped as doctors
determined he needed more surgery on his broken leg.
</P>
<P>
The two-time world champion had wished to return to training as
soon as Saturday with an eye toward the Hungarian Grand Prix in
mid-August.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher received a check for hours by doctors at a Geneva
clinic and Ferrari said in a statement after the examination that
"it is too early for him to return in an F1 car racing in the
coming weeks".
</P>
<P>
Schumacher snapped his right leg in two places in a head-on
crash into a tire wall at the British Grand Prix on July 11.
</P>
<P>
Surgeons in England operated after the crash to put a steel pin
in his leg and the 30-year-old German spent nearly a week in a
clinic outside Geneva before returning home.
</P>
<P>
Ferrari said that Schumacher might make his comeback at Monza
on September 12 after he received his operation, whose date is
unspecified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
