<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mediterranean Becomes Tropical Aquarium, Italian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The warming of the Mediterranean
Sea-partly blamed for the spread of a "killer seaweed" out from
the French coast - was confirmed in a study released here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The study, produced by the Italian government-sponsored
Institute for Sea Studies (ICRAM), showed that habitat changes had
helped the invasion of 55 species of fish from the Red Sea, up the
Suez Canal, since the start of century, and 60 from the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
Some of the newcomers were fearsome: the barracuda, which "now
has some commercial importance", the scorpion fish with its
"dreadful" spines, and the puff fish which is poisonous if eaten
sushi-style.
</P>
<P>
"A fundamental role in the spread of these tropical fish is the
temperature of the water which has risen half a degree over the
last few decades," said Franco Andaloro of ICRAM.
</P>
<P>
While earlier observers were benevolent towards the new
arrivals, even the nasty ones, researchers are now alarmed that
the tougher new kids on the block will muscle out older and
distinguished denizens, weakened by pollution and over-fishing.
</P>
<P>
Italian Environment Minister Edo Ronchi said that "the tropical
fish could run riot in the Mediterranean and lead to the
extinction of the more vulnerable native species." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
