<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pan Am Games Needs Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Games are too big,
too long and they might be too expensive.
</P>
<P>
When the athletes of the Americas meet in four years in Santo
Domingo, Dominican Republic, the Pan American Games are going to
have to be shorter and require less volunteer manpower.
</P>
<P>
And that's exactly what the president of the 13th Pan Am Games
says he's going to recommend.
</P>
<P>
"When we meet in Mexico City on Sept.16 for our debriefing, I'm
going to recommend that the size of the Games be reducted from 42
sports to maybe 28 or 30," said Don MacKenzie, the man who brought
the 13th Games to Winnipeg.
</P>
<P>
"There are way, way too many sports and way too many athletes.
We reduced the events from 435 in Mar del Plata to 330 here. But
the Games should still be smaller.
</P>
<P>
"What we need to do is look at the Olympic Program, eliminate
the sports that aren't inherent to this hemisphere and with every
one we remove, add a sport that people participate in here in the
West. That will make the Games shorter; more managable and more
affordable."
</P>
<P>
As the Winnipeg Games approach its finale this Sunday, the Pan
American Sports Organization (PASO) president Mairo Vazquez Rana
has called them "the best organized Games ever."
</P>
<P>
While wealthy nations like Canada and the United States are in
a position to use the Pan Ams for more than just a celebration of
sport, it's been painfully obvious for quite some time that
smaller nations aren't so lucky.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government was reported to have pumped at least
101.5 Canadina dollars into the Games, and a total of 22,000
volunteers became the essential part for the Games' success.
</P>
<P>
If you've paid any attention to Latin American economies
recently, you know it's going to be tougher for 22,000 in Santo
Domingo to give up their lives for 16 days.
</P>
<P>
"I'll admit that a couple of days ago, I was dragging, "
MacKenzie said. "But that's my fault. Sure, these Games could have
been finished today or tomorrow, but I'm the one who wanted them
spread out over three weekends."
</P>
<P>
That's why a shorter, smaller 14th Pan Am Games is the way to
go. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
