<HEADLINE> Goldstein Celebrates Birthday with Pan Am Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Paul Goldstein gave
himself the perfect present for a tennis player, the Pan American
Games men's gold medal.
</P>
<P>
The day after his 23th birthday, Goldstein rolled over
tournament's top seed and his American compatriot Cecil Mamiit 6-4,
0-6, 3-6 to save the blushes for the United States who had been
predicted to sweep all four tennis titles.
</P>
<P>
But only Goldstein delivered the promise, with his teammates
suffered crushing defeats in the women's singles and two doubles
competitions.
</P>
<P>
"It's been a pretty good birthday so far," he said.
</P>
<P>
The worldly young man who grew up in the Washington D.C., is
ranked 92 in the ATP Tour. After a year on the pro circuit,
including a tough four-set loss to Pete Sampras at the U.S. Open,
he has learned to deal with life when he gets down. For instance,
the last time he was burnt out, he headed to the Holocaust Museum
in D.C.
</P>
<P>
"It's powerful," said Goldstein. "When you think your life's
going bad you look at what happened to them and it puts it in
perspective."
</P>
<P>
His thirst for exploring all cultures is unquenchable and that
makes being a tennis pro ideal.
</P>
<P>
"It's such a global sport. That's what I think is the coolest
thing about tennis."
</P>
<P>
That makes the Pan Am Games real cool. He's checked out
baseball, badminton and team handball. He's made friends from all
over the Americas.
</P>
<P>
"For my career, to me (the Games) actually does present a
practical purpose," said Goldstein." One of the things the (US
Tennis Association) has been trying to do is to promote more of a
team atmosphere among the US players.
</P>
<P>
"I'd like to see an experience like this translate in a similar
form onto the tour where guys are supporting each other and
working hard for each other." 
</P>
</TEXT>
