<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IAAF Says Sotomayor Is Innocent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Italian Primo Nebiolo, president
of the powerful he International Amateur Athletic Federation (IAAF)
said Friday he is sure of the innocence of Cuban high jump
recordholder Javier Sotomayor, who was accused of cocaine doping
in the Winnipeg Panamerican games.
</P>
<P>
Nebiolo said in a telephone conversation with the Cuban athlete
mother Aurora Sanabria, that "we are conscious of his innocence.
This is a trap set to Cuba, one more."
</P>
<P>
He said that "it is known that Javier is one glory of the
island and an example, because he is one of the favorite athletes
of the people, and by discrediting him, the country is also
damaged."
</P>
<P>
The IAAF president, who called from Spain, said "this case
cannot be closed and it must be investigated to the last
consequences," because he is sure of Sotomayor's innocence.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban Olympic and world champion is a member of the IAAF
Athletes Commission because of his spotless trajectory of more
than 15 years in athletism.
</P>
<P>
Aurora Sanabria said Cuban President Fidel Castro and Vice
president Carlos Lage have called the many times champion to
support him.
</P>
<P>
Sotomayor said in his first public statement Thursday to the
official newspaper Granma that he has been "the victim of a
maneuver, of an outrage." 
</P>
</TEXT>
